1. e4 {Welcome everyone to the third part of Jobava's 1.e4 Practical Repertoire for White. In this database we will present you a venomous approach to fight against 1.e4 e5.} e5 (1... d6 {We also decided to include the Modern Philidor, which is analyzed in Chapter 1.} 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {An opening which is played also from Baadur from the Black side and here we offer a practical solution:} 4. dxe5 {We go for the endgame which is carefully analyzed with new interesting ideas.} dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4 {Here Black has three moves: the less known Bb4, the old Be6, and the main Ke8.}) 2. Nf3 Nc6 (2... d5 {Here we have the Elephant gambit. We will analyze it in Chapter 3 together with other funny gambits like the Latvian Gambit and the Damiano defence.}) (2... d6 {The Old Philidor is analyzed in Chapter 2.} 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7 6. Bf4 {And all the arising complications are solved and explained in great detail.}) 3. Bc4 {Usually Black plays here Nf6 or Bc5. We will discuss about the rare sidelines in Chapter 4.} Nf6 (3... d6 {And other 3rd move sidelines are analyzed in Chapter 4.}) (3... Bc5 {In this database, Baadur is dealing with 3...Bc5 where he offers} 4. c3 Nf6 (4... d6 {And other sidelines are analyzed in Chapter 5.}) 5. d4 exd4 6. e5 d5 7. Be2 $5 {This move has been played for the first time in 1898! From then less than 500 games have reached this position. I don't want to say that this line is completely unknown, but for sure is much less studied compared for example to the main line 7.Bb5. The idea behind Be2 is that when Black will play Bg4, as he does in the 7.Bb5 line, our knight on f3 is well-defended by our bishop.} Ne4 (7... d3 $5 {An extra possibility that Black has against 7.Be2.} 8. exf6 $1 {We will analyze the arizing complications in Chapter 6.}) 8. cxd4 Bb6 {is analyzed in Chapter 8, where the differences between these positions and the ones arising after 7.Bb5 are carefully explained.} (8... Bb4+ {is analyzed in Chapter 7.})) 4. Ng5 {Against 3...Nf6 we will go for the highly ambitious 4.Ng5.} d5 (4... Bc5 $2 {30 years ago the Traxler Variation was considered dubious and interesting at the same time, nowadays engines are just refuting it. We will speak about it in Chapter 9.}) 5. exd5 Na5 {Black's main continuation.} (5... Nxd5 {The most natural move. Now we will go for the piece sacrifice.} 6. Nxf7 Kxf7 7. Qf3+ Ke6 8. Nc3 {In Chapter 9 we will discuss this historical line, and we will try to understand if it is refuted or not according to the nowadays engines.}) (5... b5 {I dedicated a whole chapter to this fashionable line nowadays, it can all be seen in Chapter 10.} 6. Bf1 $1 {is the important retreat to remember where both} Nxd5 {the new trend} (6... Nd4 {and the old main line}) 7. Bxb5 Bb7 8. d4 exd4 9. O-O Be7 {are very carefully analyzed, I suggest some new ideas where no chess player or chess author played or reviewed so far.}) 6. Bb5+ c6 (6... Bd7 {The line which I was playing myself from the Black side is analyzed in Chapter 11.}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 8. Bd3 {The idea behind 8.Bd3 is that if Black plays h6 now, we will have the possibility to play Ne4. In fact, h6 here would already be a serious mistake for Black, but still, it is the second most common move of the position!} (8. Be2 {Is White's main continuation but practice has shown that Black is absolutely fine after} h6 9. Nf3 e4 10. Ne5 Bd6 11. d4 exd3 12. Nxd3 Qc7 $11) 8... Nd5 (8... Ng4 {This is a serious sideline, we will analyze it in Chapter 12.}) 9. Nf3 Bd6 10. O-O {And here Black has 2 main concepts divided into 2 chapters:} O-O (10... Nf4 {With the idea to take on d3 and ruin our structure is analyzed in Chapter 13.}) 11. Re1 {Historically Black was playing here moves like Re8, Qc7, or Bg4. Around 10 years ago engines started to show the strong 11...f5 and from then it became by far the main line.} f5 $1 {We will analyze it in great detail in Chapter 14.} *

