1. e4 e5 {Welcome to this lesson, where I will try to explain the core of this database, and after only a 15-minute time investment you will be ready to play the lines in your blitz games or over-the-board games. Still, if you want to play it at a high level, I recommend you to analyze the rest of the database :) Let's start!} 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The Italian Game, here Black has two main options: 3...Bc5 or 3...Nf6.} Nf6 {is more challenging from the theoretical point of view, because we suggest the concrete 4.Ng5 line.} (3... Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 {We go for the so-called 'Max Lange Attack' where White tries to expand immediately in the center instead of defending the e4 pawn.} exd4 6. e5 d5 7. Be2 $5 {A rare, but very interesting and venomous direction, compared to the main 7.Bb5.} Ne4 {Black's main move by far.} (7... d3 {is the extra line that we need to study, since after 7.Bb5 d3 is not possible. Here we need to go for the concrete line:} 8. exf6 (8. Bxd3 $2 {This would be a huge mistake because the e5 is very weak.} Ng4 $15 {Black is already slightly better.}) 8... dxe2 9. Qxe2+ Kf8 (9... Be6 {is a mistake, because} 10. fxg7 Rg8 11. b4 $1 {very important move, and Black struggles to finish his development.}) 10. Bg5 Qd6 {is the main move.} (10... gxf6 {This is too risky, Black's king is in danger.} 11. Bh6+ Kg8 12. O-O {[%csl Rg8]}) (10... Qe8 {is a solid choice.} 11. Qxe8+ Kxe8 12. fxg7 Rg8 {And now I offer the novelty} 13. Bh6 $1 {The right way to support the pawn, because} (13. Bf6 {runs into} Be7 $1 {and Black is fine.})) 11. O-O Bg4 12. Nbd2 {A very interesting position arises that is much deeper analyzed in Chapter 7.}) 8. cxd4 {Now Black has 2 options:} Bb6 {is the main line.} (8... Bb4+ 9. Bd2 {We cover with the bishop, as 9.Nd2 is not desirable.} Nxd2 10. Nbxd2 O-O 11. O-O {Black's main problem here is that the knight on c6 and the bishop on b4 are quite misplaced, if we'd imagine a scenario where Black has played Ne7-c6-Ba5-Bc7 followed by f6, he would be completely fine, but it is not so easy to achieve that. Let's see some lines:} f6 {This is Black's main idea, challenging our pawn center.} (11... Bg4 {This is not great.} 12. h3 Bh5 13. Nb3 $14 {Followed by Rc1-Nc5.}) 12. a3 (12. exf6 $6 {Don't make this positional error, after} Qxf6 {Black is completely fine, even slightly better.}) 12... Ba5 {This is the right retreat.} (12... Be7 {This is not ideal for Black, since both the bishop and the knight want the e7 square, having a knight on e7 and the bishop somewhere else is more desirable.}) 13. Bb5 {is the move analyzed in great detail in Chapter 8, where White uses the fact that ...fxe5 is met by Bxc6! intermezzo, maintaining control of the e5 square.} (13. b4 {We don't go for the seemingly nice expansion on the queenside, because Black is in time to play} Bb6 14. Nb3 fxe5 15. dxe5 a5 16. b5 Ne7 {And suddenly the bishop and the knight became both very strong pieces.})) 9. Nc3 O-O 10. O-O {Comparing to the main line of the Max Lange Attack with 7.Bb5, there .7...Bg4! would be very strong, pinning our knight on f3. In this position, it is clear that 7...Bg4 is less strong because there is no pin.} Be6 {The idea of this move is very tricky: Black defends the d5 pawn so he can recapture ...Qxf6 later.} (10... Bg4 11. Be3 f6 12. exf6 {Here Black cannot recapture the queen, because his d5 pawn is hanging.} Nxf6 13. Re1 Qd6 {To continue with Rae8 is normal, but we go for} 14. h3 Bh5 15. Ne5 $1 {Our last chance to play for something, but a very good one. Black needs to be careful.}) (10... f6 11. exf6 {Again we use the fact that Black cannot take with the queen.} Nxf6 (11... Nxc3 $2 {This would be very bad for Black.} 12. bxc3 Qxf6 13. Qb3 {We achieve a good structure against Black's bishop without even wasting any tempos. White has a big initiative here.}) 12. h3 {Against ... Bg4 ideas.} Qd6 13. Be3 Bf5 14. Rc1 {And White can continue with Na4 and Bb5 and enjoy a slightly better position, at least from the practical point of view.}) 11. Be3 f6 12. exf6 Qxf6 13. Bd3 {Now we target the knight on e4, which was not possible when the bishop was on g4.} Nxc3 14. bxc3 Bg4 15. Be2 {After Black played ...Nxc3 bxc3 we achieve the desired structure against the bishop on b6 which is now locked out of the game. We have wasted some time to achieve this on Bd3-Be2, but also Black wasted on playing ...Be6-Bg4. Pluses and minuses, overall it's a good playable position for White, with better chances.}) 4. Ng5 d5 (4... Bc5 {This is called the ''Traxler Variation'', I will just quickly show the refutation.} 5. Bxf7+ Ke7 6. Bc4 $1 {[%cal Ch7h6,Cg5f3,Cd7d6,Cc4e2,Cc8g4] is the strong move, not on b3, because in the future White can easily parry the pin on g4-d1 with the move Be2.}) 5. exd5 Na5 (5... b5 {Now we need to remember a very important move:} 6. Bf1 $1 {Only here! Not on e2, because it runs into ...Nd4 and not Bxb5, because after. ..Qxd5 the pawn is hanging on g2.} Nxd5 {This is the modern line.} (6... Nd4 {This is the old line of this gambit.} 7. c3 Nxd5 8. cxd4 Qxg5 9. Bxb5+ Kd8 10. O-O {And now a very forced variation is coming} Bb7 11. Qf3 Rb8 12. dxe5 Ne3 13. Qh3 Qxg2+ 14. Qxg2 Nxg2 15. d4 {We have a better ending with a pawn up.}) 7. Bxb5 Bb7 {This position is very topical nowadays.} 8. d4 exd4 9. O-O Be7 10. Qh5 g6 11. Qh6 Qd7 12. Re1 {And now Black needs to remember the move} a6 (12... Qf5 13. Bd3 {White is much better.}) 13. Ba4 Qf5 {Now Bd3 is impossible.} 14. Nf3 O-O-O 15. Bxc6 Bxc6 16. Nxd4 Qf6 17. c3 $14 {is the novelty I offer, not taking on c6 and leaving the choice to Black.} Rhe8 {is the best move for Black.} (17... Bb7 {is a mistake because of the simple move} 18. Nd2) 18. Na3 {With arising complications where White is ahead.} Bxa3 $2 {is not possible due to} 19. Bg5 {Winning material.}) (5... Nxd5 {If Black takes the pawn there is a very famous variation.} 6. Nxf7 Kxf7 7. Qf3+ Ke6 8. Nc3 Ncb4 {And now it is very important to remember the next moves.} 9. O-O c6 10. d4 $1 {If not d4 we are worse, but with this move, we can play for an advantage and it is very difficult to play with Black, especially over the board.}) 6. Bb5+ c6 {This is the established main line.} (6... Bd7 7. Qe2 {This line was considered dubious for Black, but engines have found a new interesting idea. I was also playing this line from the Black side, but I stopped because I didn't like the position.} Bd6 8. O-O h6 {Black needs to include this move.} (8... O-O 9. Nc3 {And we can retreat to the nice e4 square if Black troubles us with ...h6.}) 9. Nf3 {We don't want to go to e4 if we are forced to take back with the queen.} O-O 10. Bxd7 Qxd7 11. Nc3 c6 {This is Black's new idea.} 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Qxe5 cxd5 14. d4 Nc6 15. Qf4 {We have an interesting position, where White is a pawn up and Black needs a lot of only moves to stay in the game. I played a mistake from the Black side (15...Rfe8) and offered a draw, the best is} Rae8 16. Qd2 {A very classy move and our idea is to go Nd1-c3 next, since ...Re4 is not a problem anymore.}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 8. Bd3 {Now Black's main options are to attack the knight on g5.} (8. Be2 {We don't play this move because we are not in touch with the e4 square and after} h6 9. Nf3 e4 10. Ne5 Bd6 {it was proved by practice (thousands of games) that Black is fine here.}) 8... Nd5 (8... h6 {A lot of players are messing up the moves, this is a mistake to remember.} 9. Ne4 {The big difference between 8.Bd3 and 8.Be2.}) (8... Ng4 9. Nh3 {is my recommendation.} (9. Ne4 {is the main line where a lot of crazy variations ensue.} f5 10. Be2 $1 h5 $1 11. h3 fxe4 12. hxg4 Bc5 {I also give this position to study as an alternative and analyzed in the database also.}) 9... Bd6 (9... Bc5 {Now this move is dubious, even if the bishop looks active on c5, it is not great.} 10. Nc3 O-O 11. O-O {And our position is better, after a move like} h6 {the idea is to play} 12. Kh1 $1 {and when the Black knight retreats from g4 to attack our knight on h3, we also react.} Nf6 13. Ng1) 10. Nc3 (10. O-O $6 {We don't play this, because Black has the important trick:} Nxh2 11. Kxh2 e4+ {And he is fine.}) 10... O-O 11. O-O {And now the same trick is not possible anymore.} e4 $14 {This is the best move.} (11... Nxh2 12. Bxh7+ $1 {Big difference.} Kxh7 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Kxh2) 12. Nxe4 Bxh2+ 13. Kh1 Bc7 14. f4 {A new position where I like White's chances.}) 9. Nf3 Bd6 10. O-O {And here Black has two main directions:} O-O (10... Nf4 11. Nc3 {It is crucial for Black to take the bishop immediately.} Nxd3 (11... O-O 12. Be2 $1 {This is possible now because Black doesn't have ...e4 anymore.}) 12. cxd3 O-O {A very complicated position, we are a pawn up, but it's not the greatest, but also Black's knight on a5 is missing out on the action for the moment.} 13. Re1 Re8 (13... c5 {Black can play without ...Re8, but it's difficult.} 14. b3 Nc6 15. Ba3 Bg4 16. h3 Bh5 17. Rc1 f5 18. Nb5 {And the complications favour White.}) 14. Ne4 c5 {Black needs this move.} (14... Bf8 15. b4 $1 {is possible.} Bxb4 16. Qa4 {And our pieces get very active.}) (14... f6 15. d4 $1 {is a typical reaction to sacrifice the doubled pawn.}) 15. b3 Bf8 16. Ba3 Nc6 (16... f5 {This move was only played in correspondence chess.} 17. Ng3 Nc6 18. Rc1 f4 19. Ne4 Bg4 20. h3 Bh5 21. g4 fxg3 22. Nxg3 {A lot of interesting things are happening here, but if you remember till here it is enough.}) 17. Rc1 {Very interesting position, maybe some of you have seen it from the Candidates of 2023, where Caruana, an expert theoretician has messed up the line with} Nb4 {is Black's best move.} (17... f5 $2 {is a huge mistake.} 18. Nxc5 Qd5 19. Qc2 {Nakamura was immediately winning.}) 18. Bxb4 cxb4 19. Ng3 {or 19.Nc5. Both moves are possible, maybe Black equalizes in the end, but still from the practical point of view it is very dangerous to play.}) 11. Re1 {This is the main line, where Black used to play some passive moves like ...Qc7/Re8.} f5 {In 2013, engine showed this move, and since then it has been considered the best Black has in this position and a very topical line.} (11... Bg4 {is an example of a move played in the past.} 12. h3 Bh5 13. Bf5 $1 {A creative way to unpin the knight on f3.}) 12. Nxe5 Qf6 13. Nf3 {Here we have a very forced long variation where White sacrifices a piece for a lot of pawns.} g5 14. c4 Nf4 15. Bf1 g4 16. d4 gxf3 17. Qxf3 Ne6 18. Qc3 {Until here it was forced, here Black has a choice.} Nxd4 {Giving the piece back is probably Black's best.} (18... Qh4 19. h3 c5 (19... Nxd4 20. c5 {White is better, because at some point the c4 square will be available for the bishop.}) 20. Qxa5 Nxd4 21. Nc3 f4 {And here I offer} 22. Rd1 $5 {Now the ...Nf3 resource doesn't work anymore.} (22. Re4 {Not this move, because Black has the strong} Nf3+ $1 23. gxf3 Bxh3 {And Black will achieve a perpetual.}) 22... Nf3+ 23. gxf3 Bxh3 24. Ne4 $1 {The key idea, controlling the g5 square and after} Rf7 25. Qc3 Rg7+ 26. Qxg7+ Kxg7 27. Rxd6 {White is winning, because Black sacrificed too much material.}) (18... Nb7 19. c5 Bc7 20. b4 {White gains space and has a very interesting position with 3 pawns against a piece.}) 19. c5 Be5 (19... Bc7 {Hanging on to the piece is quite bad after} 20. b4 Rb8 {is already a very difficult move, with the idea to meet bxa5 with ...Be5.} 21. f4 {We stop the idea and White has good chances here.}) 20. Qxa5 f4 {The topical move, here Black won two games in practice.} (20... Nc2 21. Bg5 $1 {is the move to remember here a very interesting position arises after} Qxg5 22. Rxe5 Nxa1 23. Bc4+ Kh8 24. f4 {Only two pawns for the rook, but the difference in piece activity is immense, and the knight on a1 will be captured at some point anyway.} Qf6 (24... Qxf4 $4 {This is a terrible blunder.} 25. Qc3 {And White is already winning.}) 25. Nd2 {And we will play Qc3-b3 and will only be an exchange down for one pawn.}) 21. Nd2 Bf5 22. Qa4 $14 {is the new idea I discovered. After} Nc2 23. Nf3 $1 {we sacrifice the exchange.} Nxe1 24. Nxe5 Qxe5 25. Bxf4 {And here Black needs to be very careful since the knight on e1 will be lost and we will have a bishop and 3 pawns vs a rook.} *

