1. e4 d6 {This is a repertoire about 1...e5, but as in the Modern Philidor Black is playing e7-e5 anyway, and we are anyway checking the Old Philidor, we felt it would be logical to include also the Modern Philidor} 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 (3... Nbd7 {Black typically starts with 3...Nbd7 when aiming for the Philidor Defense but wishes to avoid the endgame that arises after 3...e5 4.dxe5. Therefore, it is crucial to have a plan against this move order.} 4. f4 $1 {The most principled continuation.} e5 5. Nf3 exd4 6. Qxd4 $1 {A very important move to remember. This move is particularly powerful because Black has already committed to Nbd7, eliminating the possibility of playing Nc6.} (6. Nxd4 $6 {Is natural but a mistake.} g6 {Where Black has already a good game.}) 6... c6 7. Be3 d5 $1 {The critical continuation.} ({Black cannot just play normal moves, otherwise he will end up in a much worse position.} 7... Be7 8. O-O-O O-O {And now White can immediately strike in the center.} 9. e5 $1 Ng4 10. Bg1 dxe5 11. fxe5 Nb6 12. Qe4 $18 {White is dominating the position. A potential plan could involve playing h3, followed by Nh6 and g4, effectively limiting Black's knight on h6 for the foreseeable future.}) 8. e5 Ng4 {Black's most logical continuation as it forces our bishop to retreat on g1.} (8... Bc5 {Would make White's life easier.} 9. Qd2 $1 (9. Qd3 $6 {Looks also good, but in fact here Black is fine.} O-O $3 {And the main difference is that we cannot play Bxc5-Nxc5-exf6 because or Qd3 would be attacked by Black's Nc5. At the same time the immediate exf6 is not good because after Bxe3 we cannot take back Qxe3 because of Re8.}) 9... Bxe3 10. Qxe3 Ng4 11. Qd2 Qb6 12. h3 $1 Qe3+ (12... Ne3 $6 13. Bd3 $16 {Black should already think about how to save his Ne3.}) 13. Qe2 $14 {A nice idea. The point is that after Qxe2-Bxe2, when Black plays Ne3 our Bf1 is not attacked.} Qxe2+ 14. Bxe2 Ne3 {Is critical, but doesn't work.} (14... Nh6 15. g4 $16 {Black's Nh6 is out of the game.}) 15. Kf2 Nxc2 $2 16. Rac1 Nb4 17. a3 Na6 18. Bxa6 bxa6 19. Na4 Bb7 20. Nd4 Rc8 21. Nf5 $18) 9. Bg1 Bc5 (9... Qb6 {Black is much worse also in the endgame.} 10. Qxb6 axb6 11. h3 Nh6 12. g4 $16) 10. Qd2 Bxg1 11. Rxg1 Qb6 12. Na4 $1 {An important move, forcing Qe3+.} Qe3+ 13. Qxe3 (13. Qe2 $2 {Be careful, in the 8...Bxc5 line we were playing Qe2 against Qe3+, but now the f4 pawn is hanging. In the 8...Bxc5 variation Black couldn't take Qxf4 because his Ng4 was attacked by our h3 pawn.}) 13... Nxe3 14. Bd3 {White is better, for example:} b5 15. Nc3 Nc5 16. Ke2 Nf5 17. Bxf5 $1 Bxf5 18. g4 Bd7 19. b4 Na6 20. a3 $16 {White enjoys a great space advantage, and also Black's Bd7 and Na6 are very passive.}) 4. dxe5 {A pleasant and practical choice that will be particularly annoying for most Philidor players.} (4. Nf3 {is the main line.} Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O {There are approximately 20,000 games in this position, with many possible tricky move orders. While White can certainly fight for an advantage, we believe that aiming for the endgame is a more practical choice.}) 4... dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4 Ke8 {When Philidor players realized that life is not so easy for them after 6...Be6, 6...Ke8 became the main move.} (6... Bb4 {is not very popular, but it's a solid option for Black. Now White has a choice between two directions.} 7. Bd2 $5 (7. Bxf7 {Is the critical move, but if Black is precise then he achieves just a little bit unpleasant but defendable endgame.} Rf8 (7... Nxe4 8. Nge2 Rf8 {transposes}) 8. Bb3 Nxe4 9. Nge2 {Now Black can take the f2 pawn with the knight or with the rook, but none of these captures is good for him.} Nc5 $1 (9... Nxf2 $2 10. Rf1 Ng4 11. Bg5+ Ke8 12. Rxf8+ Bxf8 13. O-O-O $16 {White had a decisive lead in development, as happened in the game Korneev-Torres 2013.}) (9... Rxf2 $2 {Loses immediately.} 10. Ng3 $1 Nxg3 11. hxg3 $18 {Bg5+ and Rxh7 are coming next and Black in serious trouble because of his lack of development and because his king becomes a target.}) (9... Bf5 {is the more common move.} 10. Be3 Nd7 11. O-O-O Nxc3 12. Nxc3 c6 13. Ne2 $14 {White is slightly better because of Black's worse structure. We can continue with c3 and then Ng3 trying to obtain the important e4 square for our knight.}) 10. Bc4 Be6 11. Bxe6 Nxe6 $14 {We can continue with Be3-000. Black's position is unpleasant but objectively defendable.}) 7... Ke7 ({Would be a big mistake for Black to give up the bishops pair.} 7... Bxc3 $2 8. Bxc3 Nxe4 9. Bxe5 $16 {White has the better development but also the bishops pair advantage.}) 8. Nf3 Nbd7 (8... Bd6 {is also possible, not obstructing yet the Bc8.} 9. Nh4 $5 {is an interesting way of dealing with the ...Be6 idea. We are ready to meet it with Nf5+.} g6 {is the critical response, continuing his plan.} 10. O-O-O Be6 11. Bxe6 Kxe6 {Comparing to the 6...Be6 line, here Black's structure remained intact, but it doesn't mean that his suffering is over.} 12. g3 $14 {We plan to continue with f4. The squares around Black's king became quite vulnerable, and after we bring our rook to f1, White can create serious threats.}) 9. O-O-O c6 (9... Rd8 10. Bb3 $14 {We are waiting for c6 and only later we will play Nd5+ so that after Nxd5-exd5 we wil have dxc6 options.}) 10. Nd5+ $1 Nxd5 11. exd5 Bxd2+ 12. Nxd2 $14) (6... Be6 7. Bxe6 fxe6 {In the past the general opinion about this position was that Black is fine because his doubled 'e' pawns are actually controlling some important central squares. Nowadays the assesment has changed and it has become clear that White has some advantage because in the long run, Black's 'e' pawns are more a weakness than a strenght, especially the e5 pawn can become a problem.} 8. f3 $1 {A very important move. We defend our e4 pawn and limit Black's f6 knight. But also we are preparing the Nh3-Nf2-Nd3 maneuve to target the weak e5 pawn.} Bd6 {Black defends the e5 pawn and is ready to continue with Ke7.} (8... Bc5 9. Nd1 $1 {Thanks to the modern engines this move became a standard idea of this variation. The point is that when Black plays the natural Nc6 White will be able to play c2-c3 taking control over the important d4 square. Nd1 can be useful later on the e3 square.} Nc6 10. c3 Ke7 11. Nh3 Rad8 12. Ke2 $16 {Nhf2-Nd3 next}) (8... Nc6 9. Nb1 {In this case computer likes more the retreat on b1, with the idea that after Nd4 White can play Kd1.} (9. Nd1 $5 {is also possible.}) 9... Nd4 10. Kd1 $16 {White will continue with c3 and then with the standard moves Nh3-Nf2-Ke2.}) 9. Nh3 $1 {As already mentioned our plan is Nh3-Nf2. If you liked the Nb1 idea you can play 9.Nb1 as well.} Ke7 10. Nf2 Nc6 11. Be3 a6 {Generally played to avoid Nb5 ideas.} 12. Nb1 $14 {Again we can use this very strong idea. We want to play c2-c3 covering the d4 square and then we continue with Nd2 and eventually Nc4, from where together with Nd3 our knights will pose problems to the e5 pawn.}) 7. f4 $5 {Nowadays this concrete move is posing great problems to the Black's position.} Bb4 {The most critical continuation. By pinning our Nc3 Black is directly targeting our e4 pawn. With such an important tension between the central pawns, it's clear that the position becomes very concrete now.} (7... Bd6 {Black has also tried to support his e5 pawn.} 8. Nf3 {Using the fact that exf4 is impossible due to the e4-e5 fork.} Nbd7 (8... Nc6 {Allows an unpleasant pin.} 9. Bb5 $1 Nd7 {Has to be played in order to support the e5 pawn.} 10. g3 $1 {White simply protects his f4 pawn and enjoys a slightly better position. Don't forget that Black will not be able to castle anymore.} a6 {Sooner or later Black has to play it, as it's very hard to see an alternative continuation. Moves like Ke7 are not great of course because of Nd5+.} 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Be3 $14 {Black has the bishops pair, but as known the a+c+c structure is ideal for a knight. We can continue with normal moves like long castle, double our rooks on the 'd' line and play the standard Na4.}) 9. O-O $1 (9. g3 {is White's most common move, but after the strong} Bb4 $1 10. O-O Nb6 $1 {Engine thinks that Black was already able to solve some problems.}) 9... c6 {A standard move. Black is taking control over the important d5 square. Now he wants to continue with Ke7 or even with b5 if possible.} (9... exf4 {Doesn't work.} 10. Nb5 $1 Nxe4 11. Re1 f5 12. Nxd6+ cxd6 13. Bxf4 $16) 10. a4 $1 {Against b7-b5 ideas.} Ke7 11. g3 $14 {You may think that it's not so easy to break Black's position, but try to think how to continue with Black...}) (7... Nc6 8. Nf3 Bd6 {transposes to 7... Bd6.}) 8. Bd3 {We really need to play this passive-looking move in order to protect our e4 pawn.} Nbd7 {Is considered nowadays Black's best direction. It's very logical as Black is ready for Nc5 which puts some pressure against our e4 pawn.} (8... Nc6 {Was the old main line, but now it became clear that Black is not equalizing here.} 9. Nf3 Bg4 10. fxe5 $1 Nd7 11. Bf4 {Supporting the e5 pawn. Now Black has to give up the bishops pair in order to gain back the important central pawn.} Bxf3 12. gxf3 Ndxe5 {More precise in my opinion because after 13.Be2 now Black can play Rd8 not allowing White to play long castle.} (12... Ncxe5 13. Be2 $14 {White enjoys the bishops pair advantage. The idea behind moving our light squares bishop again is to defend the f3 pawn and continue with long castle.}) 13. Kf2 $14 {We are ready for Nd5. If Black wants to stop it he needs to give up the bishops pair.} (13. Be2 $6 {not great now, because after} Rd8 $11 {White cannot play anymore long castle}) (13. O-O-O $5 {An interesting dynamical direction.} Bxc3 {Black must first exchange on c3 in order to take the f3 pawn} (13... Nxf3 $2 14. Nb5 $16) 14. bxc3 Nxf3 15. Bb5 $1 (15. Bxc7 Kd7 $1 16. Bf4 Ke7 $11) 15... Rc8 16. Rhf1 Nh4 17. Rd5 $36 {White has a strong initiative for the sacrificed pawn because the 2 bishops are dominating the board and Black's king is potentially weak as he has lost castling rights.})) ({Black doesn't have an improved version of the 7...Bd6 line if he now plays} 8... Bd6 {because now White can play concretly} 9. fxe5 $1 Bxe5 10. Nf3 $16 {and thanks to our Bd3 Black cannot play Bxc3-bxc3-Nxe4.}) 9. Nf3 Nc5 10. O-O Bxc3 $1 {Has been seen in only three games, but it's Black's most critical continuation.} (10... exf4 {Black's most common continuation.} 11. Bxf4 {Black's c7 pawn is hanging.} c6 (11... Nxd3 {Taking the bishop pair doesn't help Black.} 12. cxd3 c6 13. a3 Be7 14. d4 $14 {Position would be more or less fine for Black if he could castle, but with a king stuck on e8, this position is very unpleasant.}) 12. a3 $5 {Forcing Black to decide immediately if he wants to take on c3, as it will be his last chance to do it.} Ba5 (12... Bxc3 13. bxc3 {Black has damaged White's structure, but the bishops pair are more an important factor here. Of course, Black can play Nxd3, but then our structure would be strong again.} Be6 {Has been seen in the game Van Foreest-Doboue 2021.} 14. Nd4 $14 {And Black's position is just worse. For example:} Ncxe4 (14... Rd8 15. Bg5 $14) 15. Bxe4 Nxe4 16. Rae1 {Black is in big trouble.} Nxc3 (16... Nf6 17. Nf5 $16) 17. Nf5 Rg8 18. Be5 Nd5 19. Nxg7+ Ke7 20. Bd4 $16 {White's active pieces are making the difference. +1, 80 according to the engine.}) 13. b4 Nxd3 14. cxd3 Bb6+ 15. Kh1 $14 {Same story, that the only problem Black really has is his king, ...Ke7 can be met with the unpleasant Bg5! Otherwise, we plan to expand in the center or on the queenside with moves like Na4 or a4-a5.}) 11. bxc3 Nfxe4 {Black managed to take our central e4 pawn. Of course for a human eye, this looks very risky for him, but it's approved by the strongest engines.} 12. Re1 Nxd3 {Only move.} 13. cxd3 Nd6 $1 {Objectively Black will achieve a defendable position, but White has some different tries.} (13... Nxc3 $2 14. Bb2 $18 {White has a crushing lead in development.}) 14. c4 $5 {The second time this position was reached in practice, the strong GM Pechac was prepared and tested his opponent in an other critical line.} (14. Nxe5 {in the first game White took back the pawn, Djukin-Kadric 2023, but now Black has the strong} Kd8 $14 {Not an easy move to find. But if Black knows it then he is fine.} (14... Be6 $6 {Was the game continuation, and now White missed the strong} 15. g4 $16 {that is already posing a big amount of problems.})) (14. Ba3 $14 Be6 15. Rxe5 Kd7 16. Nd4 g6 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Rae1 Rae8 19. c4 $14 {/= White has some pressure but the endgame is defendable for Black.}) 14... Be6 15. Bb2 (15. Rxe5 $14 {another interesting try} Kd7 16. Nd4 g6 (16... Rae8 {logical but risky} 17. f5 Bxf5 18. Rxe8 Rxe8 19. c5 Bxd3 20. cxd6 $14 {and Black needs to prove his compensation for the missing piece.}) 17. Bb2 Rhe8 18. Kf2 $14 {/=}) 15... exf4 16. Bxg7 Rg8 17. Be5 Kd7 18. Bxf4 $14 {1/2-1/2 Pechac,J (2580) -Baidetsky,V (2478) SVK-chT 2324 Slovakia 2023 (9.1) Black should be able to hold but White enjoys a risk-free pressure.} *

