1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 {A rare guest in nowadays chess, but still a line with more than 20K games with a lot of history behind.} 3. d4 exd4 (3... Nc6 $6 {is a bad idea, because after} 4. Bb5 {We are transposing into a Spanish where Black has played 3...d6, a known dubious line. Let me just remind you that d6 variations are possible against the Spanish, but it's better for Black to start 3...a6 4.Ba4 and play 4...d6 only now, because after White plays d2-d4 Black has now b7-b5 ideas.} exd4 5. Nxd4 Bd7 6. Nc3 Nf6 (6... g6 7. Be3 {I like here the idea of playing with Qd2 and long castle. Also after Black moves his knight from g8 we can play Bh6.} Bg7 8. Qd2 Nf6 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Bh6 O-O 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. O-O-O $16) 7. Bxc6 $1 bxc6 (7... Bxc6 $6 8. Qd3 {White ignores the bishop on c6 and focuses on fast development.} Be7 9. Bf4 O-O 10. O-O-O $16 {It is an even worse version for Black since he can't generate any counterplay on the queenside despite his intact structure.}) 8. Qf3 {Black has now the bishops pair, but he is not in time to finish his development without making concessions.} c5 (8... Be7 $6 9. e5 $16 {Nxc6 next.}) 9. Nf5 {Our knight on f5 is very strong and Black has nothing better than to exchange it giving up the bishop's pair.} Bxf5 10. exf5 $1 {An important move to remember.} (10. Qxf5 Qd7 $13 {Is more acceptable for Black.}) 10... Be7 11. g4 $16 {We can continue with Bf4-000 having a better position and very easy play.}) (3... Nf6 {is an old line where Black achieves a very unpleasant endgame.} 4. dxe5 Nxe4 5. Qd5 $1 Nc5 6. Bg5 Be7 (6... Be6 7. Qxc5 $1 dxc5 8. Bxd8 Kxd8 9. Ng5 $16) 7. exd6 Qxd6 8. Nc3 $1 Qxd5 (8... Bg4 $6 {Not trading on d5 doesn't help Black.} 9. Qxd6 {Most precise.} Bxd6 10. Nb5 Bxf3 11. gxf3 $18 {And White achieves a winning advantage after capturing the second bishop on d6.}) 9. Nxd5 {White is clearly better in the endgame.} Bd6 10. Be3 $1 {Usually White plays long castle, but this move is crushing according to the engines.} Ne6 11. Nd2 $16 {Nc4 next and Black is much worse.}) (3... Bg4 {was popular around 100 years ago, but now it's absolutely clear that after} 4. dxe5 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 dxe5 {White enjoys the advantage of the bishops pair, and after a move like} 6. Qb3 $16 {Black has also development issues.}) (3... Nd7 {is known as a bad move order to achieve the Philidor.} 4. Bc4 {And now it's not so easy for Black to finish his development.} c6 (4... Ngf6 $2 {A losing move.} 5. dxe5 dxe5 (5... Nxe5 6. Nxe5 dxe5 7. Bxf7+ $18) 6. Ng5 $18) (4... h6 {Against Ng5 ideas, but it's too slow.} 5. dxe5 dxe5 6. Bxf7+ $3 {Is winning for White. We could stop here, but I want to show you a possible line.} Kxf7 7. Nxe5+ Kf6 8. Nc3 $1 Kxe5 9. Qd5+ Kf6 10. Qf5+ Ke7 11. Nd5+ Kd6 12. Bf4+ Kc6 13. Qe6+ Bd6 14. Nb4+ Kb6 15. Bxd6 $18 {My job is done. Now you need to remember and convert a +7,00 advantage.}) (4... Be7 $2 5. dxe5 dxe5 (5... Nxe5 6. Nxe5 dxe5 7. Qh5 $18) 6. Qd5 $18) (4... exd4 {Black can still transpose to exd4 type of positions, but then his Nd7 is misplaced.} 5. Qxd4 $5 {We can take now with the queen because Black doesn't have Nc6 ideas comparing with the 3...exd4 line.} Ngf6 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Bf4 $1 {As we will see later in this chapter, this is White's best square to develop his Bc1.} O-O 8. O-O-O Nb6 {And here I like the simple} 9. Rhe1 $5 {and when Black takes our bishop} Nxc4 10. Qxc4 Be6 11. Qe2 $16 {We have a very easy-to-play position. Nd4 next followed by f3-g4 for example. Engine evaluation is already close to +1,00.}) 5. O-O Be7 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Ng5 $1 Bxg5 (7... Nh6 $2 8. Ne6 $1 fxe6 9. Bxh6 $18) 8. Qh5 Qe7 9. Qxg5 $16 {White has the bishops pair and Black is also behind in development.}) 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7 (5... g6 {is an old system.} 6. f3 {Our idea is to continue with Be3-Qd2-000 in a Dragon Sicilian style. If you think about it now actually we have on the board a Dragon Sicilian but with the difference that Black's pawn is on c7 instead of e7. This detail is bad for him because the open 'c' file is important for him in the Sicilian, While here the only chance for him to justify would be to play c7-c5 at some point, but as we will see this is not doing much.} Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 Nc6 (8... d5 {Of course first of all we need to check what happens after the immediate central strike, but it just doesn't work for Black.} 9. e5 $1 Nfd7 (9... Ne8 10. Bg5 $1 Qd7 11. O-O-O Bxe5 12. h4 $16) 10. Bg5 $1 Qe8 11. O-O-O c6 (11... Qxe5 12. Ndb5 $16) 12. f4 Nc5 (12... f6 {Opening up files is a bad idea for the side with no development.} 13. exf6 Nxf6 14. Re1 $1 {Unpleasant tempo, Black doesn't have a good square for the queen.} Qf7 15. Bd3 $18 {Black will struggle to reach move 30. After 15... h6 you can retreat or leave the bishop there, it's up to you. White's attack is crushing through.}) 13. h4 h6 14. Bf6 $18) (8... Re8 {Black's idea might be to take control over the e5 square, so that after d6-d5 White doesn't have e4-e5 anymore.} 9. O-O-O d5 {But now White is much better after} 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Bg5 $18 {And the engine already shows a winning advantage.} Qd7 12. Ne4 $1 {is the only move to win, but it is easy enough to find.}) 9. O-O-O Nxd4 (9... Re8 10. g4 Ne5 11. g5 Nh5 12. f4 Ng4 13. Bg1 $18 {Simply cannot work for Black.}) (9... d5 {Black plays exactly like in the Dragon Main line.} 10. Nxc6 {Not the only move, but I want to highlight a typical resource White has in these positions.} bxc6 11. Bc4 $1 {Uses the pin and also the fact nobody can support the d5 pawn with a move like ...e7-e6.} Be6 12. Bb3 $16 {Black pawns are well under control, but our majority will soon start marching.}) 10. Bxd4 Be6 {Here we can see that Black doesn't have enough resources to create some counterplay.} 11. g4 c5 {With Qa5 ideas.} 12. Be3 Qa5 13. Bh6 $1 Bxh6 (13... Bxa2 $2 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Nxa2 Qxa2 16. Qc3 $18) 14. Qxh6 b5 15. Bxb5 Rab8 {Here many moves are possible. I like the straight-forward} 16. h4 Rxb5 17. Nxb5 Qxb5 18. h5 Rb8 19. b3 $16 {Where according to the engine White is winning and also from the practical point of view our play is very easy.}) (5... Nc6 {transposes to 3...Nc6?! after} 6. Bb5) 6. Bf4 $1 {The best square for our c1 bishop in these structures.} O-O 7. Qd2 d5 {Is the critical line, but if White remembers Black is just worse.} (7... c6 8. O-O-O b5 (8... d5 {is an inferior version of the 7...d5 line, but maybe still Black's best shot.} 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 $16 {Where after the queen recapture, both 11.Kb1 and 11.Nb3 offer a big advantage.}) 9. f3 b4 10. Na4 Bd7 (10... c5 11. Nb5 $16) 11. g4 c5 12. Nf5 $1 Bxa4 13. Nxe7+ Qxe7 14. Bxd6 $16) (7... Nc6 8. O-O-O Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Be6 10. f3 {We have already seen this type of positions in the 5...g6 variation. Here doesn't change much, White is just better, for example:} a6 (10... Nd7 11. h4 $16) 11. g4 b5 12. h4 c5 13. Qe3 b4 14. Na4 Qa5 (14... Qc7 15. g5 Nh5 16. Bh2 $16) 15. b3 Bd7 16. g5 $1 Nh5 17. Bh2 Bxa4 18. bxa4 Qxa4 19. Bc4 $18) (7... a6 8. O-O-O b5 9. Be2 $5 b4 (9... Bb7 10. Nf5 $16) 10. Nd5 $16) (7... Re8 {is just a waste of time.} 8. O-O-O Nc6 9. f3 $16 {with an excellent position.}) 8. Ndb5 $1 Bb4 (8... c6 $2 {A bad move order} 9. Nc7 Bb4 (9... d4 10. Nxa8 dxc3 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. bxc3 Nxe4 13. Bd3 Bd6 14. Bxd6 Nxd6 15. O-O-O $18) 10. f3 $16) 9. O-O-O c6 10. Nc7 Nxe4 11. Qd4 {Now Black has two options.} Nxc3 (11... Bxc3 12. bxc3 Qe7 13. c4 Qa3+ 14. Qb2 Qa5 15. cxd5 Nxf2 16. Be2 Na6 17. Nxa8 Nxh1 18. Rxh1 Nb4 19. Bc4 Qc5 20. Bd2 Nxd5 21. Bxd5 Qxd5 22. Re1 $16) 12. bxc3 Ba3+ 13. Kb1 Bg4 (13... Na6 14. Nxa8 Qa5 15. Bxa6 bxa6 16. Ka1 c5 17. Qe5 $18) 14. f3 Be6 15. Nxa8 Qa5 (15... Na6 16. Bxa6 bxa6 17. Qxa7 $18) 16. Bd2 Na6 17. c4 Bb4 18. cxd5 Bxd5 19. Bxb4 Nxb4 20. Bc4 $16 {Okay, we can conclude the chapter here. 7...d5 is the only challenge in the Old Philidor, and we have seen that White is able to get a big advantage in every line. The rest are very dubious and you should remember just that our attack is much faster and stronger.} *

