1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 f5 {This is known as the "Latvian Gambit", before computer era it was played from time to time, now of course Black's life is much more difficult.} (2... d5 {This is called "Elephant Gambit".} 3. exd5 e4 (3... Bd6 4. d4 e4 5. Nfd2 Nf6 6. c4 O-O 7. Be2 $16) 4. Qe2 Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7 6. Nxe4 O-O {and now it's very important to remember the exact refutation:} 7. Nxf6+ $1 (7. d4 Nxd5 {Black has some compensation}) 7... Bxf6 8. d4 $1 (8. d3 $4 Re8 $19) 8... Qxd5 9. Be3 Nc6 10. Qb5 $16 {long castle next and White will keep his extra pawn.}) (2... f6 {I think this line is called "Damiano defence"} 3. Nxe5 $1 Qe7 ({Of course if Black plays} 3... fxe5 {after} 4. Qh5+ g6 5. Qxe5+ $18 {White is immediately winning.}) 4. Nf3 d5 5. d3 dxe4 6. dxe4 Qxe4+ 7. Be2 Bf5 8. Nc3 $1 {This important move is the refutation.} Qxc2 9. Qxc2 Bxc2 10. Nd4 Bg6 11. Bf4 $18 {already +3,00 according to the engine}) (2... Bc5 {This gambit also gained some popularity because of the online chess boom.} 3. Nxe5 Nc6 4. Nxc6 dxc6 5. c3 $1 {if White plays d2-d4, Black can just resign} Qh4 6. Qf3 Qh6 {a funny idea that prevents for the moment d2-d4 as White's Bc1 is undefended} 7. b4 Bb6 8. Na3 $16 {d4 next and White is winning.}) (2... Qe7 {The Russian GM Shimanov is playing a lot this line in online blitz games, we'll not speak too much about this move, as Qe7 is clearly misplaced.} 3. Bc4 d6 4. d4 $5 Bg4 (4... Nf6 5. Nc3 $16) 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. Be3 Nbd7 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 $16) 3. Nxe5 Qf6 {Black's idea is to take back fxe4 and then play Qg6-Nf6} 4. d4 d6 5. Nc4 fxe4 6. Nc3 Qg6 {This is the starting position of the Latvian Gambit, here the modern engines' refutation is} 7. Ne3 (7. f3 {is the main line, and it's also a good direction.}) 7... Nf6 8. Be2 {Black is not down in material, but White's idea is to play 00 followed by f2-f3 and Black's position should collapse.} c6 (8... Be7 $2 9. Ncd5 $1 Bd8 10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 {forced, otherwise White has Bh5} 11. O-O O-O 12. f3 $18 {and Black is too much behind in development on the queenside.}) 9. O-O Be7 10. f3 O-O (10... exf3 11. Bd3 $1 Qh5 12. Rxf3 O-O 13. Nf5 $16) 11. fxe4 Nxe4 12. Bd3 Rxf1+ 13. Qxf1 d5 14. Qf3 $16 {White is winning a pawn.} *

