1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {Black's main moves are 3...Nf6 and 3...Bc5, and you will face one of these 2 moves in the 99% of your games. In this chapter we will check Black's sidelines at move 3.} d6 {This is probably Black's most sensible sideline.} (3... f5 {Black plays in the Jaenish style e4 e5 Nf3 Nc6 Bb5 f5, but here White will have a big advantage as Bc4 is much better placed on the just weakened a2-g8 diagonal.} 4. d4 exd4 (4... fxe4 5. Nxe5 d5 6. Bb5 $16 {White will continue with c2-c4 and eventually castle followed by f2-f3.} Qd6 7. c4 $16) 5. e5 $16 {White is much better. In the Jaenish variation a lot of times White is spending a move for Bb5-Bc4, here we will be just a full tempo up in an already half-dubious line.}) (3... Nd4 {Black sets a trap, and you need to be careful because Nxe5 would be a huge mistake.} 4. Nxd4 (4. Nxe5 $2 Qg5 $1 {Where we will see a famous cute checkmate.} 5. Nxf7 Qxg2 6. Rf1 Qxe4+ 7. Be2 Nf3#) 4... exd4 5. O-O $16 {White is much better. He can continue with c2-c3 and then build a strong center.}) (3... g6 {This variation is playable against the Spanish, but here it doesn't work.} 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Nxc6 bxc6 {In the Spanish White's bishop is on b5 and after bxc6 it gets attacked, now White is just a full tempo up.} 7. O-O Ne7 8. Nc3 O-O (8... Rb8 9. Be3 Rxb2 $2 10. Bd4 O-O 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. Qd4+ f6 13. Bb3 $18) 9. Be3 {We just play normal moves and Black's position is worse by itself.} d6 10. Bd4 $16) (3... Be7 {Black's idea is to play Nf6 next but avoid with this move order the dangerous 4.Ng5 variation. His problem is that now after 4.d4 White has an improved version of the Max Lange variation.} 4. d4 $1 exd4 (4... d6 {is very passive.} 5. d5 {I like this positional direction.} Nb8 (5... Na5 6. Bd3 $16 {Black's Na5 is misplaced.}) 6. Bd3 $1 {An important move because we want to be able to answer c7-c6 with c2-c4 supporting our center. We have reached a type of position where nobody would play with Black against 1.d4. Compared to the king's Indian Black will not be able to develop his bishop on g7 exactly because of the move 3...Be7.} Nf6 (6... c6 7. c4 Nf6 8. Nc3 $16) 7. c4 O-O 8. Nc3 Nbd7 9. h3 $5 {A useful move, with the idea that when we play Be3 Black doesn't have Ng4 ideas.} Nc5 10. Bc2 c6 11. Be3 $16) 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 O-O 7. O-O Nxd4 (7... d6 8. Bf4 {soon or later Black will need to take on d4 anyway.}) 8. Qxd4 d6 9. Bf4 $14 {We have reached a very good version of the positions analyzed in the Old Philidor chapter.}) (3... h6 {Black intends to play Nf6 next, but wants to avoid the 3...Nf6 4.Ng5 variation. Again his problem is that 3...h6 is not useful against the Max Lange.} 4. d4 $1 exd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 {For example after} Bb4 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. O-O {Black is having a hard time because after 8...00 White can play 9.e5!, while after} d6 {White can anyway play} 9. e5 $1 dxe5 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Bxf7 $14 {Where he enjoys a much better structure, and also after Bxc3 bxc3 Black's structure is still worse, but White also has the bishops pair advantage.}) 4. d4 Nf6 (4... Bg4 {Doesn't work because after} 5. h3 Bxf3 6. Qxf3 {White is threatening mate on f7.} Qf6 7. Qb3 $18 {Leads to a decisive advantage.}) 5. d5 $1 {The critical move. We grab some space and also gain a tempo against Black's Nc6.} Nb8 (5... Ne7 {Black wants to continue with Ng6-Be7-00.} 6. Bd3 Ng6 7. h4 $1 {Immediately challenging Black's Ng6.} Be7 (7... h5 {Weakens too much the g5 square.} 8. Ng5 $16) (7... Bg4 {Black prevents the h4-h5 push, but after} 8. Bb5+ $1 {White will anyway manage to achieve it.} Nd7 9. h5 $16) 8. h5 Nf8 9. h6 g6 10. c4 $14 {Black's position reminds a very bad King's Indian Defence.}) 6. Nc3 (6. Bd3 {Compared to the 3...Be7 variation, now Black could play g6-Bg7 in a King's Indian style. Still White should be better but we will suggest a different direction.}) 6... Be7 {Against Nc3 with White's pawn still on c2 usually it's better for Black to develop with Be7. The reason behind this principle is that when White's pawn is still on c2, Black's Bg7 is forever passive because even if the center opens one day, White can always play c2-c3 limiting Black's Bg7.} (6... g6 {Is not a great idea now, because White is very fast in creating some play on the queenside.} 7. h3 Bg7 8. a4 $16) 7. a4 O-O (7... a5 $6 {Weakens too much the b5 square.} 8. Be3 $16) 8. a5 c6 9. O-O cxd5 {This position has been reached in the game Nepo-Artemiev 2022, but now I like} 10. exd5 $14 {Then we continue with normal moves like h3-Be3 and we have for sure the better position.} *

