1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 {Black's huge main line.} 4. c3 {As we will see in the next Chapters, we don't really want to play in Gioco Piano style, but we want to go for the immediate c3+d4. In this Chapter we will check the alternatives to the main line 4...Nf6.} d6 {Black's best sideline for sure.} (4... Qe7 {I would never check this move if Carlsen wouldn't have played it once in a Titled Tuesday.} 5. d4 Bb6 (5... exd4 6. O-O $1 {White is ready for cxd4, while if Black plays dxc3 then after Nxc3 we are ready also for the Nd5 jump with tempo.} dxc3 7. Nxc3 $18) 6. O-O d6 7. a4 a6 8. h3 Nf6 9. Re1 $16 {I know that we are not going to play the Gioco Piano, but in this case, we have an extra tempo because we have played d2-d4 immediately (without d2-d3) and Black has played the strange Qe7, and it means we are at least a tempo and a half up compared to the standard lines.}) (4... Qf6 {funny, but suspicious move} 5. d4 $1 {the energetic refutation} exd4 6. e5 Qg6 (6... Nxe5 $4 {just loses a piece} 7. Qe2 d6 8. cxd4 $18) 7. cxd4 Bb4+ 8. Nc3 d5 $1 {Black's only move to not lose immediately.} (8... Qxg2 $4 9. Rg1 Qh3 10. Bxf7+ $18 {typical tactic}) 9. Be2 Nge7 (9... Qxg2 {is not really winning a pawn as we can capture the g7 one.} 10. Rg1 Qh3 11. Rxg7 $16) 10. O-O $16 {I don't think this position needs too many comments. Compared to what we will see in the next chapters this is just a dream position for White as Black's knight is on e7 instead of e4 and also Qg6 is not great.}) (4... Bb6 {doesn't have independent value, because after} 5. d4 exd4 (5... Qe7 {transposes to 4...Qe7}) 6. cxd4 d6 {transposes to 4...d6}) 5. d4 exd4 (5... Bb6 $6 {allows} 6. dxe5 $1 {this was considered winning for White just until 1-2 months ago, where the game Theodorou-Hakobyan showed that Black can still have some little hope to stay in the game.} Bg4 {Black tries to play for compensation, but after} (6... dxe5 7. Qxd8+ {and White will win either the f7 or the e5 pawn}) (6... Nxe5 7. Nxe5 dxe5 8. Bxf7+ $18) 7. exd6 Nf6 $1 (7... cxd6 $2 {Black doesn't have time to take back the d6 pawn} 8. O-O Nf6 9. Bf4 $16) 8. O-O O-O 9. Bg5 {this position was reached only in the very recent game Theodorou-Hakobyan, and it is probably the only direction if Black wants to try to rehabilitate the 5... Bb6 line (without exd4)} h6 10. Bh4 g5 11. Bg3 Nxe4 12. dxc7 Qc8 $14 {engine's novelty} (12... Qxd1 $2 13. Rxd1 Nxg3 14. hxg3 Bxc7 {this is how the mentioned game continued, but here I like} 15. Na3 $16 {and White is just a pawn up}) 13. Qd3 $5 Bf5 14. Qd5 $14 {New position that needs to be investigated, but for sure Black is the one who needs to prove a lot.}) 6. cxd4 Bb6 (6... Bb4+ $2 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. O-O O-O 9. Nd5 {White already has an important advantage.} Nxe4 {May look critical, but after} 10. a3 Ba5 11. b4 Bb6 12. Re1 {White is already winning.}) 7. h3 $5 {against Bg4 ideas} (7. O-O {would allow} Bg4 {where maybe White can still fight for something after} ({if} 7... Nf6 8. h3 {is White's best move anyway}) 8. Bb5 {, but no sense to start with 7.00 if anyway we are going to play h3.}) 7... Nf6 8. O-O $1 (8. Nc3 $6 Nxe4 $1 {and Black is immediately fine.}) 8... O-O (8... h6 $2 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Re1 $16 {White is just much better}) (8... Nxe4 9. Re1 O-O {trans} (9... d5 $4 10. Bxd5 Qxd5 11. Nc3 $18)) 9. Re1 $1 {now Black absolutely needs to break White's center} (9. Nc3 $6 Nxe4 $1 10. Nxe4 d5 $11) 9... Nxe4 $1 (9... d5 $6 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Bg5 {White has a fantastic version of the isolated pawn because all of his pieces are very active} Qd6 12. Nc3 Be6 13. Ne4 Qd7 (13... Qb4 $2 14. Rc1 $18) 14. Ne5 $16) 10. Rxe4 d5 11. Bxd5 Qxd5 12. Nc3 {Comparing to 9...d5 here Black has managed to exchange his knight for White's light squares bishop, clearly something that is he happy about} Qd8 13. d5 {We just have a position where Black is by far not lost and can play, but it's clear that he didn't equalize, for example:} Ne7 (13... Bf5 14. Re2 {flexible move, maybe one day we will need to double the rooks on the 'e' file, and also f2 is more defended now} Ne7 15. Bg5 f6 16. Qb3 $1 Kh8 17. Be3 $16) 14. a4 $14 {just to take some space on the queenside} a5 {now the b5 square is weaker} 15. Bg5 f6 16. Bf4 $14 {We can build up the pressure on Black with moves like Qb3-Rc1-Nb5 and sometimes watch out for tactical ideas like d6 push or retreating the rook from e4 to c4!} *

