1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 exd4 ({Black doesn't have other possible moves, for example if} 5... Bb6 6. dxe5 Ng4 {White is winning after} 7. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 8. Ng5+ Ke8 9. Qxg4 Nxe5 10. Qg3 $16) 6. e5 d5 ({Again Black doesn't have other options, for example:} 6... Ng4 $2 7. cxd4 Bb4+ 8. Nc3 $18 {White will play h3 next with an already winning position.}) (6... Ne4 $2 7. Bd5 $1 f5 (7... Nxf2 8. Kxf2 dxc3+ 9. Kg3 $18) 8. cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 $16 {Now that Black has played f7-f5, our d5 bishop is a monster and Black cannot even castle short.}) 7. Be2 $5 {An interesting less known direction. 7.Bb5 is White's main move and it leads to the famous Modern Max Lange Attack. We will speak about the merits of 7.Be2 in the next chapters, I can already say that one idea is that when Black plays Bg4 our Nf3 is not under the pin. Besides me, this line was played a lot by Levon Aronian and Jeffrey Xiong. I think this is a line that has a lot of venom, and by playing it you need to study much much less theory compared to the mainstream variations against 1.e4 e5.} d3 {This is an extra option that Black has after 7.Be2} 8. exf6 {I like the arising messy positions, White's position is slightly better from the practical point of view. From experience on the Black side, I can tell you that nobody is really comfortable playing with a White's pawn on f6!} (8. Bxd3 $6 {would be a mistake, because after} Ng4 $15 {our e5 pawn is a weakness.}) 8... dxe2 9. Qxe2+ Kf8 $1 (9... Be6 $6 10. fxg7 Rg8 11. b4 $1 {A very important move because Black needs to decide where to retreat his bishop and we will act accordingly} Be7 {logical, against Bg5 ideas} (11... Bb6 $2 12. Bg5 Qd6 13. Nbd2 $1 (13. Bf6 $2 {Aronian-Nakamura 2018, but Black is fine after} Qf4 $36) 13... Rxg7 14. O-O $18 {equal material but Black's king cannot castle, for example, if} Kd7 15. b5 Ne7 16. Bf6 $18 {Ne5+ next.}) (11... Bd6 12. Bg5 Be7 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. b5 $1 {One of the merits of the move 11.b4, is that after we play b4-b5 Black's knight c6 doesn't have a lot of good squares to move.} Na5 15. O-O O-O-O 16. Nd4 Qf6 (16... Rxg7 $4 17. Nf5 $18) 17. Nd2 Rxg7 18. Rfe1 $16) 12. b5 Na5 13. O-O Rxg7 14. Re1 $14 (14. Bf4 {has been played by Piorun against Sasikiran in 2017, but now Black can try to simplify the position:} Bd6 $1 {White is still a little bit better after} 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Re1 O-O-O 17. Nbd2 $14 {at some point g2-g3 to not allow Black any counterplay on the 'g' line.}) 14... Bd6 (14... Nc4 {Bringing the knight into play is a sensible idea, but too slow.} 15. Nbd2 Qd6 (15... Nd6 16. Nd4 $16 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gd2f3] We managed to activate both of our knights while Black only improved one piece.}) 16. Nxc4 dxc4 {And if Black had one more tempo to play .. .0-0-0 he would be more or less fine, but we are in time for:} 17. Bh6 $1 {Important tempo.} Rg6 18. Rad1 $1 {We stop castle long, and Black's position is very dubious.} Qc5 19. Bf4 $16 {Ne5 next}) 15. Ba3 $5 {can be a more convenient trade, because after Black takes on a3 we can maneuver faster our Na3 to c2 and d4} (15. Be3 Qe7 16. Bd4 Rg8 17. Nbd2 $14) 15... Qe7 (15... Bxa3 16. Nxa3 Qd6 17. Nc2 $16) 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. g3 $16 {White has an extra tempo compared to the 14.Bf4 line}) 10. Bg5 ({after} 10. fxg7+ Kxg7 11. O-O Re8 $11 {Black is completely fine as happened in Kristensen-Shirov 2018.}) 10... Qd6 {Black wants to continue with normal development like Bg4-Re8.} (10... gxf6 {is too risky for Black, after} 11. Bh6+ Kg8 12. O-O $14 {White has a long-term compensation due to Black's exposed king and to the very passive Rh8.}) (10... Qe8 {is a solid choice, with the idea to enter in an endgame:} 11. Qxe8+ Kxe8 12. fxg7 Rg8 {now it's White who has an extra pawn, but Black has the bishops pair, so we really need to keep our strong g7 pawn.} 13. Bh6 $14 (13. Bf4 {if we don't defend our g7 pawn, then Black is completely fine after} Rxg7 14. Bxc7 f6 15. Bg3 Re7+ 16. Kd2 d4 $44) (13. Bf6 {could look more logical, but Black has the strong} Be7 $11 {solving all the problems.}) 13... f6 {Black wants to play Kf7-Kg6.} (13... Ne7 {with Nf5 idea to take back the g7 pawn} 14. Nbd2 Nf5 15. Bf4 c6 16. O-O Rxg7 17. Rfe1+ Kf8 18. Nb3 $14 {Nbd4 next and White has a slightly better position.}) 14. Nbd2 Kf7 15. O-O Kg6 16. Bf4 $1 {As you have already noticed we are ready to give up the g7 pawn but attacking the c7 pawn at the right moment.} Bb6 $1 (16... Rxg7 {looks logical, Black takes the pawn and defends c7, but after} 17. Nh4+ $1 {it turns out that Kf7 would leave the c7 pawn hanging, while} Kh5 18. Ndf3 $40 {is potentially dangerous for Black. Just imagine h3-g4+ coming and it's almost mate.}) 17. a4 a5 18. c4 $14 {/= we are still sitting on the more pleasant side, but Black should be able to slowly equalize}) 11. O-O Bg4 12. Nbd2 Re8 (12... h6 13. fxg7+ Kxg7 14. Be3 {is the known path.} (14. Bh4 $14 {is another interesting direction} Rae8 15. Qb5 a6 16. Qa4 Bxf3 17. Nxf3 Re4 18. Qb3 {The point is that we have a better version of the 12...Re8 line, as Bh4 was a useful move, while h7-h6 not really.}) 14... Rae8 (14... Rhe8 15. Qd3 Bxe3 16. fxe3 $14) 15. Qd3 Bxe3 16. fxe3 $14 {We can double our rooks on the 'f' line and personally I don't have doubts that White is preferable, at least from the practical point of view.}) 13. Qb5 $5 {and Black needs to think about the b7 pawn, but also about his development.} a6 $1 (13... Bb6 $6 14. Rae1 $14) 14. fxg7+ (14. Qxb7 $4 Na5 $19) 14... Kxg7 15. Qa4 Bxf3 $1 {An important move because Black wants to use the e4 square for his rook.} 16. Nxf3 Re4 $1 17. b4 Bb6 18. Bh4 $14 {We want to continue with Bg3 next. According to the engine Black is fine, but in a practical game, I would take White because Black's king is potentially exposed.} *

