1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. e5 d5 7. Be2 Ne4 8. cxd4 {Here Black has a choice between the more common Bb6 and the more rare Bb4+.} Bb4+ 9. Bd2 (9. Nbd2 $6 O-O 10. O-O Ba5 $1 {Black will maneuver his bishop to b6 entering in a sort of 8...Bb6 variation where White's knight is misplaced on d2. According to engine, this is already -0,15 for Black!}) 9... Nxd2 (9... Bxd2+ {Black can also choose to exchange the dark squares bishops, but then White just has a pleasant game} 10. Nbxd2 O-O 11. O-O Bf5 (11... Bg4 12. a3 $14 {a typical useful move with the idea to play b4-Nb3 taking important space on the queenside}) (11... f6 12. Bb5 Bg4 13. Qa4 Nxd2 14. Nxd2 Ne7 15. Bd3 fxe5 16. dxe5 $14) 12. Re1 $14 {is more precise according to the computer, with the idea Nf1-Ng3} (12. Rc1 Qe7 {this is how the game Jobava-Adams EU 2021 continued})) 10. Nbxd2 O-O 11. O-O {Black has the bishops pair but his problem is that his Nc6 + Bb6 are a bit misplaced. Black's Nc6 has a clear future on the e7 square, Whilte Bb4 has three possible futures: - go to a5 and then to b6 where it will be a bit passive, but at least it will attack the d4 pawn - after Black plays f6-exf6-Qxf6 his bishop can go to the good d6 square - it can just say on b4 and eventually go to e7 if attacked. In this last scenario, Black tries to do some other things instead of thinking about his bishop, but from the positional point of view it's not a great outcome for him because Be7 is doing nothing, and also the e7 square is needed for Nc6.} f6 {Black's most logical move. After exf6-Qxf6 Black's Bb4 would have available the ideal d6 square.} (11... Ne7 {This clearly shows that Black is ready to play Ba5-Bb6.} 12. a3 Ba5 13. b4 Bb6 14. Nb3 {at this point Black's only idea is to play f6} f6 (14... Ng6 15. Bd3 $14 {and Black is not in time for f6 as Bxg6 with a great structural damage would be coming.} (15. Re1 $6 f6 $11)) 15. exf6 Rxf6 16. Rc1 c6 17. Re1 $14 {Black has the nice e5 and c5 squares for his knights.}) (11... Bg4 {doesn't solve the problem of Bb4+Nc6.} 12. h3 Bh5 (12... Bxd2 $2 {As always a bad idea.} 13. hxg4 Ba5 14. g5 $16 {g3-Kg2 next and Black's situation is critical.}) 13. Nb3 $14 {Rc1-Nc5 next.}) (11... Ba5 {can be a good idea because it avoids the a3+b4+Nb3 construction.} 12. Nb3 (12. a3 {doesn't make sense now, because after} Bb6 $1 {White is not in time anyway for the a3-b4-Nb3 construction.}) 12... Bb6 13. Bb5 {necessary move, to delay a bit f7-f6} (13. Rc1 f6 $11) 13... Ne7 (13... f6 $2 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. h3 $16) 14. Re1 f6 15. exf6 Rxf6 16. Re3 $14 {Qe2 or Qe1 next} a6 (16... Bg4 {would try to solve problems directly, but White has a strong initiative after} 17. Qe1 $1 Bxf3 18. Rxe7 Bh5 19. Nc5 $14 {And even with little material it is unpleasant to deal with the active rook on e7.}) 17. Bd3 Bf5 (17... Nf5 18. Re5 $14) (17... Bg4 $4 18. Bxh7+ $18) 18. Nc5 $14) 12. a3 $5 {is an interesting new try.} (12. exf6 $2 Qxf6 $15 {Black has a fantastic position, suddenly all of his pieces are very active.}) (12. Nb3 {the most common move} Re8 (12... fxe5 13. dxe5 {We are entering in some very complicated positions where really it's all about move by move.} Rf5 $1 {seems to be the only move that equalizes, engine idea is to go Rh5 next} (13... Re8 $6 14. Bb5 $14) 14. Bd3 Rh5 $1 15. a3 Bf8 16. Re1 Bg4 17. Be2 $36 {very complicated position. In my opinion and according to the engine White has a small initiative, but of course, all three results are possible.} (17. h3 {just leads to an equal position after} Bxf3 18. Qxf3 Rxe5 19. Rxe5 Nxe5 20. Bxh7+ Kxh7 21. Qh5+ Kg8 22. Qxe5 $11)) 13. Bb5 {in the past I thought White has something here, but in the 2023 World Cup Vidit showed a very precise path for the equality} Bg4 $1 14. Bxc6 {[%eval 0,0] maybe other moves are possible, but according to the engine, it's} bxc6 15. Rc1 fxe5 16. dxe5 Rxe5 $1 17. Nbd4 Re4 18. Nxc6 Qd6 {1/2-1/2 Mastrovasilis,D (2587) -Vidit, S (2719) FIDE World Cup Baku 2023 (2.8) , and now it's White that needs to be a bit careful to equalize} 19. Nxb4 Rxb4 20. h3 Bh5 21. Rxc7 $1 Rf8 22. Rc3 Rxb2 23. Qd4 $11) 12... Ba5 $1 (12... Bxd2 $2 {a big positional mistake. In this structure, it's very important for Black to generate counterplay and not to trade his pieces} 13. Qxd2 Re8 (13... Bg4 14. Rae1 $16) 14. exf6 Qxf6 15. Bb5 $16 {Bxc6-Ne5 next}) (12... Be7 {not and ideal square for Black's bishop} 13. Rc1 {White is ready to play on the queenside with moves like Bb5 and Nb3-Nc5 (eventually also b2-b4) .} (13. Bb5 $6 {Now this doesn't work, because} fxe5 $1 {is much stronger since the bishop is not hanging on a5.} 14. Bxc6 e4 15. Ne5 bxc6 16. Nxc6 Qe8 17. Nxe7+ Qxe7 $11 {And position is around balanced since our knight is much more passive on d2.}) 13... fxe5 14. dxe5 Kh8 15. Bb5 (15. Re1 $14 {even stronger according to the engine, but I also like 15.Bb5.}) 15... Bd7 {happened in the game Warmerdam-Kevlishvili 2022. Now the young dutch GM went for the wrong path and has played the somehow artificial Bd3 back, I think that White has something after} 16. Bxc6 $1 bxc6 $1 (16... Bxc6 $6 {natural but bad} 17. Nb3 $16 {Re1-Nfd4-Nc5 next and White is dominating.}) 17. Nb3 Bg4 $1 18. Nbd4 Bxf3 19. Nxf3 c5 20. Re1 Rb8 21. Re2 $14 {Engine will hold, his best move is now 21...d4, but in a human game after 21.. .d4 22.Qd3 I am sure everybody would take White.}) 13. Bb5 (13. b4 $6 Bb6 14. Nb3 {looks logical but after} fxe5 15. dxe5 a5 16. b5 Ne7 $15 {Black has a very good position. If you remember I have told you that Black's problems are his Bb4 and his Nc6. Now it's clear that both of these pieces became very strong.}) 13... Ne7 (13... Nxd4 $14 {is the engine's novelty to achieve a balanced equal position} 14. Nxd4 fxe5 15. Nc2 {Black has for sure a good compensation for the piece, but it's also clear that all three results are possible now. This position has never happened and requires practice to be understood well. I would be slightly optimistic here because I think that it's Black who needs to prove compensation, and I would feel that I am not risking much here.}) (13... Bb6 $6 {allows} 14. Bxc6 $1 bxc6 15. Rc1 {Caruana-So 2019} (15. Qa4 $14 {15.Rc1 is good, but if you are scared of the computer top defensive line, you can try 15.Qa4.}) 15... fxe5 (15... a5 $14 {engine defence} 16. a4 $5 fxe5 17. Nxe5 Ba6 18. Re1 Bxd4 19. Ndf3 Bxe5 20. Nxe5 Bb7 21. Nxc6 Qf6 $1 22. Qxd5+ Kh8 23. f3 Rad8 24. Qe6 Bxc6 25. Rxc6 Qd4+ $1 26. Kh1 Qxa4 $11) 16. Nxe5 Ba6 17. Re1 Bxd4 18. Ndf3 Bxe5 19. Nxe5 Bb7 {Mastrovasilis-Sokolovsky 2021} 20. Qb3 $14 Rb8 21. Qb4 $14 {Great compensation for the pawn.}) (13... fxe5 $14 {is a bad idea, but we need to remember why:} 14. Bxc6 $1 e4 15. Ne5 bxc6 $2 (15... Bb6 $1 {Using the fact that we cannot give up the important d4 pawn.} 16. Nxe4 bxc6 17. Nc5 $14) (15... Bxd2 16. Qxd2 bxc6 17. Nxc6 $16) 16. Nxc6 {So we are just winning a piece?} Qg5 17. f4 $3 {Important detail} (17. Nxa5 $2 Bh3 18. g3 e3 $44) 17... exf3 18. Nxf3 Qe3+ 19. Kh1 Bb6 20. Nfe5 $18 {And White has a very big advantage.}) 14. Qc2 (14. Bd3 {You can also play this because somebody from inertia can play a bad move like ...Ng6. If they repeat with 14...Nc6 you can play 15.Bb5 and then choose another option.} Nc6 $11 (14... Ng6 $6 15. Bxg6 hxg6 16. exf6 Qxf6 17. Ne5 $14)) (14. exf6 $5 {also interesting now that Qxf6 is not possible.} Rxf6 15. Re1 $14 {/= later we can play b4+Nb3.}) 14... Bf5 (14... fxe5 15. Nxe5 $14) (14... c6 $6 15. Bd3 $14) 15. Bd3 Bxd3 (15... fxe5 16. Nxe5 c6 {1/2-1/2 Warmerdam,M (2619) -Kevlishvili,R (2530) NED-ch Groningen 2022 (3.3)} 17. Rae1 {I like this easy plan to double our rooks on the 'e' line, for example} Qd6 18. Re2 Rae8 19. Rfe1 $14) (15... Qd7 16. Bxf5 Nxf5 17. Nb3 Bb6 18. Nc5 $14) 16. Qxd3 Ng6 {very logical, Black puts pressure on the e5 pawn} 17. g3 c5 $1 {Ponomariov as a world-class player understands perfectly how to play this position from the Black side.} 18. b4 $1 {Very important for White to maintain his central pawns.} cxb4 19. Nb3 bxa3 20. Nxa5 Qxa5 {0-1 Vallejo Pons,F (2705) -Ponomariov,R (2723) ESP-chT CECLUB Honor Melilla 2011 (3) This was really a high-level game, here I would suggest playing the simple} 21. Rxa3 Qc7 22. Rb1 {where we are having Benko-style compensation for the pawn. We can continue later with h4-h5 and I don't think we are risking anything. The worst scenario that I can see is that Black will give a pawn to trade everything and make a draw. Keep in mind that to achieve this position Black had to play a lot of very strong moves, and so far only a strong player like Ponomariov managed to find all of them.} *

