1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. e5 d5 7. Be2 ({In the main line, after the moves} 7. Bb5 Ne4 8. cxd4 Bb6 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Be3 {is White's main attempt to fight for an advantage} (10. O-O {Black is completely fine after} Bg4 $1 {and it turns out that the bishop on e2, as it will be in our lines, is much better placed}) 10... f6 {now it's not so strong as against 7.Be2, because after} (10... Bg4 {is Black's main move, after} 11. h3 Bh5 12. Qc2 {Black has three main systems, 12...Bg6, 12...Nxc3 and 12...Na5, after each of them it's difficult for White to show something. Furthermore, Black's best move according to my engine is 12. ..f5. All in all, here Black has a big option and a lot of games were played, so it will be difficult to surprise our opponent}) 11. Qb3 fxe5 {White has the important} 12. Bxc6 $1 bxc6 13. Nxe5 {maybe Nxf2 is still playable for Black, but White can play here.}) 7... Ne4 8. cxd4 Bb6 {This is the core chapter of this database. In the 7.Bb5 line, after 8...Bb6 there are almost 4000 games, here only 250 games and this is very good news for us because it means that the lines are much less explored.} 9. Nc3 (9. O-O {is another possible move order, even if in the 99% of the cases we will play both Nc3 and 00, it's very hard to say which move order is more precise.}) 9... O-O ({Black can try to exploit our 9.Nc3 move order} 9... Bg4 10. Be3 $1 {if Black plays 10...00, after 11.00 trans to main line} (10. O-O $6 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Nxd4 12. Nxe4 Nxf3+ 13. Qxf3 dxe4 14. Qxe4 $11 {just equal}) 10... f6 $14 {is the only independent option, although it has never been played} 11. exf6 Nxf6 12. O-O {and here if 12...00 then it just transposes to the main line. Maybe Black can try some side moves like 12...Qd6 or 12...Qe7, but it's difficult to imagine him playing without short castle, so in my opinion after 9...Bg4 the game will very likely transpose into our main lines.}) 10. O-O {The starting position of our Chapter. Here Black has different moves, and according to my database White has a 55-60% score against each of them, and that's clearly a good sign for us.} (10. Be3 f6 $11) 10... Bg4 {Black's most common move} (10... f6 {let's start to analyze what happens if Black decides to challenge immediately our e5 pawn.} 11. exf6 $1 Nxf6 (11... Nxc3 $2 {Black wants to exchange on c3 in order to take back on f6 with his queen, as d5 will not be hanging in this case, but in fact, this is a very bad positional choice for him, and it has been played a few times by players like Hikaru Nakamura!} 12. bxc3 Qxf6 {Black's Bb6 is passive now} 13. Qb3 $14 {with the idea to play Bg5-Rae1 next} Be6 14. Bg5 Qf7 15. Rae1 $16 {White is much better, +0,80 according to the engine. Black doesn't really have a plan, for example, if Rae8 White can play Bc1!? with both Ng5 and Ba3 ideas. If Rfe8 White can play Bh4-Bg3 to improve his bishop.}) 12. h3 {a useful move against Bg4 ideas} Qd6 {a normal move. Black thinks that anyway Qd6 is useful, and then will act accordingly to our next move} (12... Ne7 {this is usually played with the idea to continue with c6-Bc7 at some point} 13. Na4 $14 {we can immediately target Black's Bb6 before he will be able to activate on the h2-b8 diagonal} Ne4 {Black takes the e4 square as our knights has left c3} (13... c6 14. Nxb6 axb6 (14... Qxb6 15. a4 $14) 15. Ne5 $14) 14. Ne5 {but we can also jump into a central square, after something like} Qd6 15. Nxb6 axb6 16. Bd3 Bf5 17. Be3 $14 {Black still needs to solve some practical problems}) 13. Be3 Bf5 (13... Ne7 14. Qd2 $1 {preparing Bf4} Ne4 15. Qc2 $1 Bf5 16. Bd3 $14) 14. Rc1 {a useful move because now we want to continue with Na4-Bb5} Rae8 (14... Kh8 15. Na4 Rae8 {Socko-Arabidze 2021} 16. Bb5 $14) 15. Bb5 $1 Re7 {Black decided to unpin his Nc6 in the game Petrov-Franklin 2017 but after} 16. Bxc6 $14 Qxc6 17. Na4 Qe8 18. Nxb6 axb6 $14 {White has the typical pleasant advantage of this variation (+0,50 also according to the engine) . The point is that White's king is potentially safer because of the extra kingside pawn. Potentially, White can also advance those pawns in the future. Also White has the important e5 square for his knight or eventually after the knight exchange for his bishop, While Black cannot really exploit the e4 square as White can always play f2-f3 at the appropriate moment}) (10... Nxc3 $2 11. bxc3 f6 {transposes into a bad version of the 10...f6 line}) (10... Ne7 {a typical move of these positions. Black is planning c6-Bc7 when after f7-f6 his dark squares bishop comes back into the game} 11. Be3 (11. Na4 $5 {is usually an interesting choice against Ne7, with the idea that when Black plays c6 we can take on b6 without allowing Bc7}) 11... c6 {Socko-Carlsen 2015} (11... Nf5 $6 12. Bd3 $1 Nxe3 13. fxe3 Nxc3 14. bxc3 $16 {Black has the bishops pair, but White is dominating, for example after} f6 $2 15. Ng5 $3 {is winning immediately} fxg5 16. Qh5 g6 (16... h6 17. Qg6 $18) 17. Bxg6 hxg6 18. Qxg6+ Kh8 19. Rxf8+ Qxf8 20. Rf1 $18 {+5,00 according to the engine}) 12. Qc2 $5 f5 (12... Bf5 13. Bd3 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Qd7 15. a4 $14) 13. exf6 Nxf6 14. Bd3 Bg4 {is the best according to the engine, but after} (14... Bc7 $6 {most common move} 15. Rae1 $16 {+0,80 according to the engine. Ne5 will come at the right moment, or White can improve with moves like Bg5 or Ne2-Ng3} (15. Ne5 $6 c5 $11)) 15. Ne5 $14 {Black has to find Qc8, where we can take Nxg4 Qxg4 and play something like f3 followed by Rae1 where it is clear that White is better}) (10... Bf5 11. Be3 (11. Na4 {is the most common move, but funny enough after} Bg4 $14 {my engine shows already a small advantage for Black, as he will play the 10...Bg4 lines, but with White's knight on a4}) 11... f6 (11... Nxc3 {you already know that this exchange is bad for Black, after} 12. bxc3 $16 {Black's Bb6 is out of play, while White's center only became stronger}) (11... h6 {Black has also tried to play without f7-f6} 12. Rc1 Bh7 {GM Mirzoev Azer played twice this move} (12... f6 $4 {is not possible because of the typical trick} 13. Nxd5 $18) (12... Kh8 {Black wants to continue with f7-f6 without allowing Nxd5 trick, but then the question is why he didn't play f6 immediately instead of h6} 13. a3 $5 {a useful waiting move, our idea is to play Na4 only after Black has played f6, so that after exf6 Black doesn't have Qxf6 as d5 is still hanging} (13. Na4 {immediately allows} f6 14. exf6 Qxf6 $13) 13... f6 14. exf6 Nxf6 15. Na4 $14) 13. Bd3 Kh8 14. a3 f5 15. exf6 Rxf6 {Remizov-Mirzoev now that Black has already played f7-f6 we know that} 16. Na4 $14 {becomes a good idea}) 12. exf6 Nxf6 13. h3 {and now Black's most logical move would be} Qd6 {and funny enough we have transposes to the 10...f6 line}) (10... Be6 {Black's usual idea after 10...Be6 is to play f6-exf6-Qxf6 now that d5 is defended} 11. Be3 f6 (11... f5 {just gives us some extra option, g3 is the best according to my engine, but maybe it's easier just to play exf6 transposing to the main line}) 12. exf6 Qxf6 13. Bd3 {immediately challenging Black's Ne4} Nxc3 {as usual Nxc3 is a concession, on the other hand now we have lost a few tempi because after} (13... Qg6 $14 {is Black's best defense, but it's a novelty} 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Bxe4 Qxe4 16. Ng5 Qg6 17. Nxe6 Qxe6 18. d5 Qf6 $1 19. dxc6 Qxc6 20. Qb3+ {very close to equal, but maybe White has still a small initiative because his rooks will be faster in taking control of the open files and his king is potentially safer.}) 14. bxc3 Bg4 15. Be2 {we have played Bd3 and Be2 back, losing 2 tempis just to provoke Nxc3. On the other hand, Black has lot also a tempo Be6-Bg4, but in exchange, he was able to take back on f6 with the queen. That's why it's difficult to say if we have lost 1 or 2 tempi. This is the reason why Black is not much worse even if he has played the undesired Nxc3 exchange} Rae8 (15... Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Ne7 {Black intends to continue with c6-Bc7} 17. Bc1 $5 {I really like the idea to maneuver our bishop to the a3-f8 diagonal} c6 18. Ba3 Rfe8 19. Rb1 $14 {against Bc7 ideas}) 16. a4 {A useful move. For example now Black cannot play Ne7 because of a5} (16. h3 {it's difficult to say if it's a good inclusion. I don't want to play it because now Black has a choice between Bf5 and Bh5 that may lead to different type of play}) 16... Qd6 (16... a6 17. Qb3 $14 {another interesting point of the move a2-a4 is that now we have the a2 square available for our queen in case Black will play Na5 at some point}) 17. Re1 {Just a useful move, let's follow Fier-Wojtaszek 2023 to see how the game could develop} h6 {both players are doing some useful moves. Keep in mind that this was a very recent game, october 2023, played by Wojtaszek, one of the best theoreticians in the world. This is for sure a sign of quality of Black's chosen system.} (17... Na5 18. Ra2 $14 {Ne5 next and after Bxe2 we can take back Raxe2}) 18. Qc2 $14 {I would try this useful move. My idea is to go Qa2 , or to act according to the situation} (18. Ra2 Ba5 $1 19. Rc2 {you can check how the game continued, but Black should be already fine} Qa3 20. Qa1 Qxa1 21. Rxa1 Ne7 22. h3 Bf5 23. Rcc1 Ng6 24. c4 dxc4 25. Bxc4+ Kh8 26. d5 Ne5 27. Nxe5 Rxe5 28. Bb3 Be4 29. Bxa7 Bxd5 30. Bxd5 Rxd5 {1/2-1/2 Fier,A (2574) -Wojtaszek,R (2668) FIDE Grand Swiss Douglas 2023 (1)}) (18. Qb3 Na5 19. Qa2 (19. Qb4 $5 Qe6 {Black should be fine}) 19... Bxf3 20. Bxf3 Nc4 $11) 18... Bf5 (18... Na5 19. Ne5 $14) (18... a6 19. Qa2 Ba5 20. Rac1 $14) 19. Bd3 {better to challenge now Black potentially strong light squares bishop} (19. Qa2 Be4 $13 {Black has a strong Be4 now}) 19... Be4 20. Kh1 $5 {a useful move showed by the engine. The point is that after Qg6 Black will not have Rxf3 ideas} Qg6 (20... Bxf3 $2 21. gxf3 $16 {White will have a strong attack on the 'g' line}) 21. Bxe4 Qxe4 22. Qa2 Qf5 {Bxh6 was a threat} 23. h3 $14 {Black doesn't have any active play now, the question is if we will be able to create some chances with White. You can for example double the rooks on the 'e' line and then just play. I know it's not easy to win, but you have a safe position and even engine shows +0,20 here}) 11. Be3 f6 (11... f5 $6 12. Ne1 $16 {or if you want exf6 transposing to 11...f6}) (11... Qd7 {Black cannot really equalize if he doesn't play with f7-f6.} 12. h3 Bh5 13. Qb3 $1 Bxf3 (13... Rad8 14. Rad1 $14) 14. Bxf3 Nxd4 15. Qxd5 Qxd5 16. Nxd5 Nxf3+ 17. gxf3 $14 {Black will have a difficult endgame}) (11... Nxc3 $2 {we have already discussed this exchange, and we know that it's bad for Black} 12. bxc3 $16) 12. exf6 (12. h3 {is another interesting move, but probably Black is in time to equalize after} Bxf3 13. Bxf3 fxe5 {where I have tried to check some moves for White, but Black was basically fine everywhere.}) 12... Nxf6 (12... Nxc3 {We will not discuss this move, we know that it's bad for Black, just let me say you that here White can even consider to include} 13. f7+ $5 Rxf7 14. bxc3 {because maybe one day c2-c4 becomes an option as Black will not be able to take dxc4 because of Bxc4.}) (12... Rxf6 {We haven't discussed this recapture too much, but you can agree that it looks very artificial} 13. Rc1 {White is threatening Nxd5, the typical trick} Kh8 (13... Rg6 $6 {a trick, now Nxd5 is not working} 14. Nxe4 $1 (14. Nxd5 $4 Bxf3 $19) 14... dxe4 15. Ng5 $16) 14. h3 Bh5 15. Ng5 $14 {White uses in his favour the fact that Black has recaptured with the rook.}) 13. Re1 Qd6 (13... Ne7 14. Ne5 Bxe2 15. Rxe2 $14) (13... Bxf3 $6 {a premature exchange seen in the game Kislinsky-Almasi 2013} 14. Bxf3 Ne7 15. Na4 $14 {and White will play a risk-free game with the bishops pair.}) 14. h3 Bh5 (14... Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Ne7 16. Qd2 $14 {with the idea Bf4.}) (14... Bf5 15. Rc1 {White will eventually play Bb5 putting pressure on Nc6, using the fact that Black has played Bf5 and it means he is not putting pressure against our Nf3.} Rae8 (15... Ne7 16. Ne5 $14) 16. Bb5 $14) 15. Ne5 $1 {Our last chance to fight for something. For me, this position is very critical, but only 1 game reached this point. This shows the fact that Be2 Max Lange is a very interesting practical weapon because the big majority of our opponents will not have clear ideas or experience on how to play these positions.} (15. Rc1 Rae8 $13 {Black is completely fine.}) 15... Bxe2 (15... Nxe5 $14 16. dxe5 Qxe5 17. Bxb6 axb6 18. Bxh5 Qxh5 19. Qxh5 Nxh5 20. Nxd5 {Black needs to defend an unpleasant endgame, for example} Rf7 21. Re7 Rxe7 22. Nxe7+ Kf7 23. Nd5 Ra5 $1 (23... Rc8 $2 24. Rc1 $16) 24. Nxc7 Rc5 25. Na8 b5 $1 26. Rd1 Ke6 $1 27. Nb6 Nf6 28. a4 bxa4 29. Nxa4 Rc2 {and probably Black holds}) 16. Rxe2 Rae8 17. Rc1 $5 {A useful move. Maybe White wants to play Nb5 and then Nxc6 forcing Black to double his 'c' pawns. Black is not threatening Nxe5 yet. Black needs to find a move now, for example:} Nd8 {better than Ne7 because now White cannot play Nf4} (17... Re7 {looks normal, Black wants to double on the 'e' line} 18. Nb5 (18. a3 $5 Rfe8 19. Nb5 $1 Qe6 20. Nxc6 bxc6 21. Nc3 $14) 18... Qe6 19. Nxc6 bxc6 20. Nc3 $14) (17... Nh5 {an active move} 18. a3 $5 {we want to take space on the queenside by playing b4} Nf4 $2 {is not working for tactical reasons:} 19. Bxf4 Rxf4 20. Nxc6 Qxc6 21. Nxd5 $18) (17... Ne7 18. Bf4 $14) (17... Nxe5 $2 18. dxe5 Qxe5 (18... Rxe5 19. Bf4 $18) 19. Bxb6 $18) 18. Na4 (18. Bf4 $2 Ne6 $17) 18... Ne6 19. Nxb6 axb6 20. Nd3 {We have a complicated position that is objectively close to equal. Personally, I like White but it's about taste. Engine evaluation is +0,05, but the game continues and Black is not able to kill the game.} *

