1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 (4... Bc5 $2 {I think this line is called "Traxler variation". Before the computer era, this line was considered very risky but interesting, with strong engines nowadays it's clear that it doesn't work.} 5. Bxf7+ $1 {The first thing that we need to remember is to take on f7 with the bishop.} (5. Nxf7 {We shouldn't spend too much time on these dubious lines, but let me just quickly show you Black's idea against the most natural 5.Nxf7.} Bxf2+ $1 6. Kf1 (6. Kxf2 Nxe4+ 7. Ke3 Qh4 $13) 6... Qe7 7. Nxh8 d5 $1 8. exd5 Nd4 9. d6 Qxd6 $13 {White is a full rook up, but according to the engine Black has enough counterplay to force a draw.}) 5... Ke7 6. Bc4 $1 {According to modern engines this is White's best retreat. I don't think it makes too much sense to understand why Bc4 and not Bb3, but one key idea is that after h6-Nf3-Bg4 we can go Be2 back unpinning our Nf3.} Rf8 (6... Qe8 {Black wants Qg6, but after} 7. Nc3 Qg6 8. d4 $3 Bxd4 9. Bf7 $1 {That's why Black really needs to play Rf8.} Qh6 10. h4 $18 {White is simply winning}) 7. Nc3 d6 (7... Bxf2+ $2 8. Kxf2 Nxe4+ 9. Ke1 Nxg5 10. d4 $18) 8. O-O Qe8 {A standard idea. Black wants to play Qg6 and also frees the d8 square for his king.} (8... h6 9. Nh7 $3 {Is a nice crushing idea.} Nxh7 10. Nd5+ Ke8 11. Qh5+ Rf7 12. Nb6 $18) 9. Nd5+ $1 Kd8 10. c3 h6 11. Nf3 Bg4 12. Nxf6 Rxf6 13. Be2 $1 {That's why Bc4 and not Bb3 at move 6! White will just finish his development and Black doesn't have any compensation for the missing pawn.}) 5. exd5 {5...Na5 here is by far Black's main move. 5...b5 is also interesting and will be analyzed in the next chapter. Now we will focus on the old 5...Nxd5.} Nxd5 $6 {It is known that this natural recapture is at least risky for Black.} 6. Nxf7 $1 {Trying to refute Black's opening. I don't know if objectively 6.d4 is worse, but 6.Nxf7 is so tempting that I could not refrain from choosing it.} (6. d4 $16 {Is also a good direction if you don't want to sacrifice the knight on f7.}) 6... Kxf7 7. Qf3+ Ke6 {Of course Black needs to defend his Nd5, even at the cost of a vulnerable king. If he plays a move like Ke8 then we just take on d5 and play with an extra pawn and a monster light squares bishop.} (7... Ke8 8. Bxd5 $18) 8. Nc3 $1 {If you have studied the Alapin databases, you will remember that in this same position (reached from the 2...e5 line) , with the c3 and c5 pawns included, here Black is fine as White doesn't have this key Nc3 idea.} Ncb4 {Black needs to defend his Nd5, and by playing Ncb4 he is also threatening Nxc2+.} (8... Nce7 $2 {Is not good because now that the c2 pawn is not attacked White can crush immediately with} 9. d4 $1 c6 10. dxe5 $18 {Where Black's position is immediately lost. Of course, you can train by playing this position against your engine in order to understand how to bring home the full point.}) 9. O-O $1 (9. Qe4 $2 {Has been the most common move, but after} c6 $17 {Black is already better.}) 9... c6 10. d4 $1 {A very important idea. If not d2-d4 White would be just worse.} Qf6 {Black's only defensive idea to not collapse.} (10... Nxc2 $4 {Immediately loses after} 11. dxe5 Nxa1 12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. Rd1 $18) 11. Qe2 {White is already threatening to play a3, and after Black's knight retreats to a6 f2-f4 would be crushing.} Ke7 $1 (11... Kd7 $2 {Has been the most common move, and it's understandable that Black wants to take his king away from the 'e' file. But this is just losing.} 12. dxe5 Qf5 (12... Qg6 13. a3 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Nd5 15. Bd3 Qf7 {Would lead to the same.}) 13. a3 $1 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Nd5 15. Bd3 Qf7 16. c4 $1 {White is winning, for example:} Ne7 (16... Nc7 17. f4 $18 {F5 next and Black is busted.}) 17. e6+ $1 (17. Qd2 $2 {Immediately would allow} Kc7 $17 {And White doesn't have Bf4+.}) 17... Qxe6 18. Qd2 Qd6 (18... Kc7 19. Qa5+ b6 20. Bf4+ $18) 19. Re1 Kc7 20. c5 $1 Qxc5 21. Qf4+ Qd6 22. Qf3 Nd5 23. Bb2 $18) 12. Ne4 ({If now White plays in the same way as after 11...Ke7, then after} 12. dxe5 Qg6 13. a3 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Nd5 15. Bd3 {The key difference is that Black has} Bf5 $17 {And he is already better.}) 12... Qg6 13. dxe5 Bf5 14. f3 $16 {The engine shows an evaluation of 0.60, which is already good news. Next, we want to proceed with a3 or c3. When Black's knight on b4 retreats to a6, we will capture with Bxd5, forcing Black to recapture with the c6 pawn. This allows us to play Nd6, giving us a significant initiative for the sacrificed piece. While I'm unsure if Black's position is theoretically defendable, practically speaking, I don't know many players who would enjoy playing it from the Black side. For the record, this position has never been reached in a practical game.} *

