1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 b5 {You can find around 3K games in this line, and 2K games more if you consider also the transposition after 5...Nd4 6.c3 b5. For many years it was considered a dubious line, but now very strong engines have found some defensive ideas for Black. In this Chapter we will sometimes mention an analysis made by GM Ivan Cheparinov in his recent Modernchess database "Top 10 2023 Games", where he analyzes this line for the Black side.} ({Black can also start with} 5... Nd4 {but after} 6. c3 b5 $1 7. Bf1 {transposes to the variation analyzed under the 5...b5 6.Bf1 Nd4 move order.}) 6. Bf1 $1 {Unexpected, but our only good move.} (6. Bxb5 Qxd5 7. Bxc6+ Qxc6 {Black has full compensation.}) (6. Be2 $6 {allows} Nd4 $1 {that attacks now our Be2.}) 6... Nxd5 {The move suggested by nowadays engines, and is also a very trendy choice for the brave players who are sometimes playing the 5...b5 variation.} (6... h6 $2 {is Black's second most common move, but it's a mistake.} 7. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 8. dxc6 {White is two pawns up at the moment, so Black should try to play concretely.} Bc5 9. Be2 Rf8 (9... Bxf2+ {Doesn't work.} 10. Kxf2 Ne4+ 11. Kf1 $1 Rf8 12. d3 Qd4 13. Qe1 Kg8+ 14. Bf3 $18 {as happened in the game Vallejo-Naiditsch 2007.}) 10. O-O Ne4 ({After the standard} 10... Kg8 {White can simply play} 11. d3 $16 {Keeping a huge advantage. Maybe Black will be able to take back one pawn, but for sure not two.}) 11. d4 $16 {White is ready to continue with Be3 next (or in case of Bxd4, c3 and then Be3) .}) (6... Qxd5 {A very suspicious move. Now White develops his Nb1 with tempo.} 7. Nc3 Qc5 8. Bxb5 Be7 {Black should play castle as fast as possible.} 9. d3 O-O 10. Bc4 $14 {with the idea to play Nge4 next.} (10. O-O {Looks like a very natural move, but after} Nd4 $1 11. Bc4 Bb7 $44 {Strangely enough Black keeps some compensation.}) 10... Bb7 (10... Nd4 11. Nge4 $1 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Qb6 13. c3 Nf5 14. O-O $16) 11. Nge4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Qb6 13. Be3 Nd4 14. O-O $14) (6... Nd4 {for a very long time this was considered Black's main continuation in the 5...b5 variation.} 7. c3 Nxd5 $1 {Instead of moving his attacked Nd4, Black takes a pawn and counterattacks our Ng5.} 8. cxd4 Qxg5 9. Bxb5+ Kd8 (9... Bd7 $2 {The exchange of the bishops is for sure not in Black's favour, as after} 10. Bxd7+ Kxd7 11. O-O exd4 12. d3 $18 {The material is equal but Black's position is already undefendable.}) 10. O-O Bb7 (10... Nf4 $2 {allows} 11. Bc6 $16) (10... exd4 {again Black doesn't have time to take on d4.} 11. d3 $16) 11. Qf3 Rb8 $1 {Black defends his Bb7 and is ready for some knight jump discovery against our queen.} (11... exd4 $2 {it's bad again. Black needs to spend time on pieces activity.} 12. d3 $16) 12. dxe5 $1 Ne3 $1 {Black's only hope to stay in the game.} (12... Nf4 $4 {a huge mistake.} 13. Qg3 Qxe5 14. d4 $18) (12... Nb4 13. d4 $1 {an important move to remember.} Qg6 14. d5 Bxd5 15. Rd1 Rxb5 16. Nc3 $18 {and White has a winning advantage.}) 13. Qh3 $1 {For the record, we are threatening Qd7 mate.} Qxg2+ 14. Qxg2 Nxg2 15. d4 {We are entering a pawn-up endgame where Black will try to prove some compensation because of his strong Bb7.} Be7 {allows} (15... Nh4 {allows} 16. Bg5+ Be7 17. Bxh4 Bxh4 {where Black gained the bishops pair but lost the potential for some counterplay. Now I like} 18. f4 $16 {that prevents Bf3 ideas.}) (15... f6 {Only Black's third most popular move, but probably his best chance to fight for a defendable endgame.} 16. f4 Nh4 (16... g5 17. f5 $16) 17. Be2 $1 {Against Nf3+ ideas.} Nf5 {Black will now win the d4 pawn, but he will have to solve other problems, especially because of the vulnerable Kd8.} 18. Nc3 Nxd4 19. Rd1 c5 20. Be3 $14 {Very hard to play with Black because for an engine it might be easy to defend this endgame, but for a human for sure not.}) 16. d5 $1 Nh4 (16... Bxd5 $4 {would lose immediately after} 17. Rd1 Rxb5 18. Nc3 $18 {When White will continue with Nxd5 threatening both a discovery check and the poor, now undefended, knight on g2.}) 17. Be2 Ng6 $1 18. Be3 $1 {Threatening f2-f4, as now Black will not have Bc5+, and the a7 pawn.} ({Black's idea is that after} 18. f4 {Balck wins the d5 pawn with check after} Bc5+ {because White has nothing better than Kg2, when Bxd5+ will come with check.}) 18... Nxe5 19. Bxa7 Ra8 20. Bd4 $14 {White will play Nc3 next and has a healthy extra pawn.}) 7. Bxb5 Bb7 {This position was very extensively analyzed by the strong opening theoretician GM Ivan Cheparinov in his Modern Chess course "Best 10 Games of 2023". From a practical point of view I think that it will be very hard for Black players to remember all the lines suggested by Cheparinov, but from the theoretical point of view, it was very hard for me to find a challenging idea against his analysis. However, I am very happy to present you with an idea that came into my mind after many hours of analysis. If you want to find the full Cheparinov analysis you should check it in his course, here I will limit myself to presenting you the concrete idea that I am suggesting to play.} (7... Bd7 $2 {Would be a huge mistake.} 8. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 9. Qf3+ Ke6 10. Bc4 $18 {White has an improved version of the 5...Nxd5 variation already analyzed in the previous chapter.}) 8. d4 {Cheparinov comments: "A very logical move played in order to open the position while defending the knight" and I think I couldn't describe this 8.d4 move better.} exd4 (8... Be7 $2 {is bad for Black.} 9. Nf3 exd4 (9... e4 10. Ne5 $16) 10. Nxd4 Ndb4 11. O-O O-O 12. Nxc6 Nxc6 $16 {White has an extra pawn and a better structure. Here you can choose if you want to play Qxd8 entering in an endgame, or if you want for now just to develop by playing 13. Nc3. In both cases White has a good advantage.}) (8... a6 $2 {loses after} 9. Bxc6+ $1 Bxc6 10. Nf3 $1 (10. dxe5 $2 Nb4 $44) 10... exd4 11. O-O $18) 9. O-O Be7 10. Qh5 $1 {White's most challenging continuation.} g6 (10... Bxg5 $2 11. Bxg5 $18 {Re1+ next and Black is busted.}) 11. Qh6 Qd7 $1 (11... Qd6 $2 {Is a mistake, because after} 12. Nd2 $16 {Black's Qd6 is much worse placed as White will eventually gain a tempo Ne4 or Nc4 against it.} a6 13. Ba4 f6 {as we will see this is Black's best continuation in the 11...Qd7 line.} 14. Nc4 Qb4 (14... Qd7 15. Na5 $18) 15. Ne6 $18) 12. Re1 (12. Nd2 $6 {Now it's dubious for White, because compared to the 11...Qd6 variation here after} a6 13. Ba4 f6 $15 {White doesn't have the important Nc4! tempo.}) 12... a6 $1 {It's good to first force the bishop to move out of b5.} (12... O-O-O $2 {Has been played twice, but it's just losing after} 13. Nxf7 Bb4 (13... Bf8 14. Qh3 $18) 14. Nxd8 Bxe1 15. Nxb7 $18 Kxb7 16. Nd2 $18 {Tutisani-Harutyunian 2023}) 13. Ba4 Qf5 $1 (13... Nb6 {has been played in the game Pijpers-Schoppen 2023, here White is much better after} 14. Bb3 Nd5 {And it's clear that Black has just lost 2 important tempis as White's bishop is anyway very well placed on b3.} 15. Nd2 $16) (13... O-O-O $14 {has never been tried in practice and it's not losing as it might seem, but White keeps the better chances. The variations now are quite forced.} 14. Nxf7 Bb4 $1 15. Nxd8 Bxe1 16. Nxc6 Bxc6 17. Bxc6 Qxc6 18. Qh3+ $1 {An important detail that allows us to defend our c2 pawn with check.} Kb8 19. Qb3+ Ka7 20. Nd2 {Black should not forget that he is still a pawn down, and the only possible continuation for him is to exchange on d2 and play Rb8 just later.} Bxd2 (20... Rb8 $2 21. Qc4 $16) 21. Bxd2 Rb8 {now Black will gain the b2 pawn. He will not regain the pawn as we will be able to win the d4 one, but at least he will destroy our queenside structure.} 22. Qd3 Rxb2 23. Qxd4+ Qb6 24. Qe5 $1 (24. Qxb6+ $6 Kxb6 $15 {Black has full compensation and even the initiative as the c2 pawn is going to fall.}) 24... Rxa2 $1 {Black restorest the material equality.} 25. Rc1 $14 {And here I want to add again Cheparinov's comment: "White is a bit better thanks to the safer king and the bishop against the knight".}) 14. Nf3 {we are going to gain the d4 pawn.} O-O-O 15. Bxc6 Bxc6 16. Nxd4 Qf6 17. c3 $14 {Finally we reach my idea against Cheparinov's analysis. Fortunately, after a lot of work, I have found an idea that was not analyzed by him. It looks a bit strange as we are giving Black the chance to keep his potentially strong light squares bishop, but from the other hand we have a strong Nd4, and also this time we are not going to lose our c2 pawn!} (17. Nxc6 {is the only move considered by Cheparinov. After} Qxc6 {As usually happens in this line, Black is able to win our c2 pawn. The move c2-c3 would be too dangerous because White is a lot behind in development on the queenside.} 18. Bd2 $14 Qxc2 19. Nc3 {White is a bit better but Black should be able to defend quite easily, also from the practical point of view.}) 17... Rhe8 $1 {The only move according to the engine that allows Black to fight for the equality. The point behind Rhe8 is to target our rook on e1, using our slight delay in development on the queenside and our weak first rank.} ({I can easily see a player to go for} 17... Bb7 $6 {because it's very tempting to take the opportunity to save the light squares bishop. But it's already a mistake!} 18. Nd2 $16 {N2f3 next and according to the engine White has already a +1,00 advantage. If Black plays c7-c5 we can start with Ne4, gaining a tempo on Black's queen f6, and only then play Nd4-f3.}) 18. Na3 $1 Bb7 {is Black's most logical move in my opinion. But I think it's even easier that he plays Bb7 at move 17, which, as we have already seen, is a mistake.} (18... Bxa3 $4 {Would be a huge mistake due to} 19. Bg5 $18) (18... Bf8 {is an important move to check because the line now is forced.} 19. Bg5 Rxe1+ (19... Bxh6 20. Bxf6 {Black has nothing better than Rxe1+, transposing in 19.Rxe1. The point is that Black is not winning a piece after Nxf6 because also Black's c6 bishop is hanging.}) 20. Rxe1 Bxh6 21. Bxf6 Re8 $1 22. Rxe8+ Bxe8 {Until now the line after 18...Bf8 was forced, and here I really like our next move.} 23. Bh8 $1 {A very cute move. Engine's idea is that Bh8 will be able sometimes to defend White's b2 pawn.} ({You can understand the strenght of the move 23.Bh8! if you compare it to the following line.} 23. Bh4 $6 Nb6 24. c4 $2 Bc1 $17) 23... Bc1 {Critical.} ({For example after} 23... Nb6 24. c4 Bc1 25. Ne2 $16 {White's bishop on h8 was able to make the difference.}) 24. Nc4 Nb6 25. Nxb6+ cxb6 26. b3 $14 {/= For sure Black has good chances to hold, but White has a risk free game and can play for many hours trying to convert his extra pawn.}) (18... Bd7 $5 {is another interesting move. The point is that after 19.Bd2 Bf8 White doesn't have Qh3+.} 19. Nac2 {Defending our Re1.} (19. Bd2 Bf8 $11 {White has nothing better than Qg5, where after the queen exchange Black plays f6 and after we move our bishop Black is equalizing thanks to Bxa3.}) 19... Bf8 20. Qg5 Rxe1+ 21. Nxe1 Re8 22. Nef3 {According to the engine Black should be able to equalize, but in a practical game it's enough one inaccurate move and Black will have to suffer in a pawn down position.} Qxg5 23. Bxg5 {For example here c7-c5 looks very logical.} c5 {With the idea that after our Nd4 moves, Black has access to the e2 square for his rook.} 24. Nb3 Re2 25. Rd1 Nb6 26. Nbd2 $14 {/= We want to play Be3 and let Black understand in a practical game how to continue.}) 19. Bd2 Bf8 {Again is the critical move in my opinion.} (19... Nb6 20. Rad1 Qh4 21. Qxh4 Bxh4 22. Rxe8 Rxe8 23. f3 $14 {/=}) 20. Qh3+ {The difference compared with the 18...Bd7 variation.} Kb8 21. Rxe8 Rxe8 22. Nac2 Bd6 (22... c5 $6 {If I were Black, I'd for sure consider this move.} 23. Nf3 Nf4 24. Bxf4+ Qxf4 {For a human, or at least for me, Black's play is sensible, but according to the engine it's a mistake. That's why is very easy for our unprepared opponents to go wrong in a practical game.} 25. Qd7 Rc8 26. Rd1 Bxf3 27. gxf3 Qxf3 28. Ne3 $16 {Engine shows +1,00.}) 23. Re1 Rd8 $1 {The right path for Black, he shouldn't exchange the rooks but instead try to use his one on the 'd' file.} 24. Qg4 $5 {with the idea Bg5. Let's stop here. My conclusions about the 5...b5 line are that it's not refuted, but it's very unpractical for Black because he needs to remember a lot of lines, a lot of only moves, to get this kind of pawn down positions that are holdable according to the engine. My main goal was to find a new idea over Cheparinov's analysis in order to have higher practical chances against the players who are studying that file by heart.} *

