1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 {This line was considered dubious for many years, but lately, it has become popular again and I was playing it myself from the Black side.} 7. Qe2 Bd6 {Black's best direction in my opinion.} (7... Be7 {is the old main line, but here Black's position is very unpleasant in my opinion.} 8. Nf3 $1 {Our knight did his job and it's time to come back to f3.} O-O (8... e4 {is a concrete line but it doesn't really work well for Black.} 9. Ne5 Bxb5 10. Qxb5+ c6 11. dxc6 a6 12. Qe2 $14) (8... Nxd5 9. Nxe5 (9. Bxd7+ {is another possible direction.} Qxd7 10. Nxe5 Qe6 11. Nf3 Qg6 12. d4 Qxg2 13. Rg1 Qh3 14. Rg3 Qe6 15. Qxe6 fxe6 16. Rxg7 O-O-O {Kravtsiv-Esipenko 2023} 17. Ke2 $14) 9... c6 (9... Bxb5 10. Qxb5+ c6 11. Qe2 $14) 10. Bd3 Be6 (10... Nf4 11. Qe4 Nxd3+ 12. Qxd3 {Now we take with the queen and enter a pawn-up endgame.} Be6 13. Qxd8+ Rxd8 14. d3 $14 {Black has some compensation, but it remains unpleasant to play with Black.}) 11. O-O Nf4 12. Qe4 Nxd3 13. Nxd3 O-O 14. Nf4 $14 {Thanks to the bishops pair Black has some but not full compensation for the missing pawn.}) 9. Bxd7 Qxd7 10. Nxe5 Qxd5 11. O-O Bd6 {GM Oleg Romanishin is playing a lot of this line from the Black side. White has an extra pawn but Black's hope is that his active pieces will provide enough compensation. Thanks to modern engines nowadays it seems that White is in time to ensure for himself a preferable position.} 12. Nf3 Rfe8 (12... Nc6 13. Nc3 Qh5 14. Qb5 $16 {Rudolf-Romanishin 2022}) 13. Qd1 $1 {White needs to make a last passive move, but then he can start to develop all his queenside and Black doesn't have good ideas to do something in the meantime.} c5 {Black tries to take some space and wants to continue with Nc6.} (13... Ng4 $6 {is premature due to} 14. d4 $16 {Controls the e5 square and Black has no attack.}) 14. d3 Nc6 {GM Oleg Romanishin has played 3 games here with the Black pieces. Now I like the following move} (14... Ng4 {is also bad} 15. Nc3 Qh5 16. h3 Ne5 17. Ng5 $16 {This move secures a very big advantage.}) 15. Bg5 $5 {with the idea to continue with Nbd2.} Qf5 (15... Ng4 {Now that Black's knight is not controlling the e4 square anymore, we can play} 16. Nc3 Qf5 17. Ne4 $16 {Cuenca-Romanishin 2022.}) 16. Nbd2 $5 Bc7 17. Re1 Ng4 {La Barbera-Romanishin 2024} 18. h3 $14 Nge5 19. Be3 $16 {And now we can see how useful it is the knight on d2.}) 8. O-O h6 $1 {A very important move. Black's point is that White has to play now Nf3 and it means that Nc3-Nge4 the idea is not available anymore.} (8... Nxd5 $2 9. d4 $16) (8... O-O {is Black's most common move, but here White is better after} 9. Bxd7 Qxd7 10. Nc3 $1 {The key point now is that as White's knight is still on g5, it can go at the right moment on e4 as it is supported now by Nc3.} c6 {Sooner or later Black will have to play c7-c6 in order to activate his Na5.} (10... Rfe8 11. Nge4 $16) 11. Qd3 $1 h6 (11... Be7 12. Nf3 $14) 12. Nge4 $16) 9. Nf3 O-O 10. Bxd7 Qxd7 11. Nc3 (11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Qxe5 Rfe8 13. Qg3 Nxd5 {Black has enough compensation, but even this position should be checked carefully.}) 11... c6 $1 {Black needs to play this move now. It was played for the first time by me from the Black side in 2023.} (11... Rfe8 12. d3 c6 13. dxc6 Nxc6 14. Ne4 $16) 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Qxe5 cxd5 14. d4 Nc6 15. Qf4 {According to the engine Black has enough compensation, but I think that from the practical point of view, it's hard to play for Black if White knows what he should do.} Nb4 {This is Black's most concrete move.} (15... Rfe8 {In the mentioned game I have played this move and offered a draw, but here White is better} 16. Qd2 $1 Qg4 17. Nb5 $1 {White will continue with c2-c3 and the main problem for Black is that he cannot play Re6 because White has Nc7. This is the reason why 15... Rae8 is a better choice for Black.}) (15... Rae8 $14 16. Qd2 {In his recent Modern Chess repertoire 1.e4 e5 for Black Cheparinov here analyzes only 16.Bd2, but I think 16.Qd2 is much more testing.} Qg4 $1 {Black's only move, otherwise White plays Nd1-c3 and he is much better.} (16... Re7 17. Nd1 Rfe8 18. c3 $16) 17. Nb5 Re6 {Comparing with the 15..:Rfe8 line, here White doesn't have Nc7.} 18. c3 Qg6 $1 {Again Black needs to find an only move, and this one is not easy at all.} (18... a6 $6 19. Na3 Rfe8 (19... Ne7 20. f3 Qg6 21. Re1 $16) 20. Nc2 $16) 19. Qd1 {Now the best line for both sides according to the engine is:} a6 20. Na3 Rfe8 21. Nc2 Ne7 $1 22. Nb4 Nf5 23. Nd3 Nh4 $1 24. Nf4 Qg5 25. Be3 R6e7 26. g3 Ng6 27. Ng2 Qf5 28. Re1 $13 {First of all in this long variation White had always a choice while Black had to play only moves to maintain the 0. 00 evaluation, and even here I think the game is still not over yet.}) 16. Qd2 Qf5 17. a3 Nxc2 18. Ra2 {It seems that Black is going to lose his Nc2, but with very precise moves he can survive:} Rac8 $1 19. b3 Ne4 $1 20. Nxe4 dxe4 $3 {The key point. Now we cannot take Rxc2 because Black has e4-e3. Keep in mind that everything here has never been played so I am not sure how easy will be for our opponent to find all these moves over the board.} (20... Qxe4 $2 21. Bb2 $16 {Bc3 next and Black is in deep trouble.}) 21. d5 (21. Rxc2 $4 e3 $19) 21... Rc5 (21... Rfd8 $4 {Now it's not working, because Black's Rd8 is not defended.} 22. Rxc2 e3 23. Rxc8 $18) 22. d6 Qc8 $3 {Again only move} 23. Qd1 $36 {With the idea to play Bf4 next. If Black makes the other 5/6 best engine's moves he will probably equalize, but I don't believe this will ever happen.} *

