1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 (7... Nxc6 $6 {Black brings back his knight into the game, but now White has an extra tempo if comparing to the main lines, as now there is no need to move the Bb5.} 8. d3 Bc5 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. O-O O-O 11. Nd2 $14 {White maintains the extra pawn. Black has some, but not full compensation.}) 8. Bd3 {The idea of this move is that after 8...h6 White's Bd3 is supporting Ne4.} (8. Be2 {Is White's main theoretical move but after} h6 $1 9. Nf3 e4 10. Ne5 Bd6 {After many years of practice it's already clear that Black has full compensation here.}) 8... Ng4 {This is Black's second-best move in my opinion. Still, I think that White has a lot of interesting directions here, and for this reason 8...Nd5 is a more serious move. If we speak from a correspondence chess point of view, 8...Ng4 is a playable line, if we speak about over-the-board chess then 8...Ng4 is very risky because White has three interesting options, in all three cases engine will hold, but the arising positions are very impractical for Black, and also he needs to remember a lot in order to reach those positions!} (8... h6 $6 {This is Black's best move in the 8.Be2 line, because after Nf3 Black can play e5-e4! with a good game. But now White can play} 9. Ne4 $1 {and it's clear that Black made a mistake because he mixed the 2 variations 8.Bd3 with 8.Be2.} Nd5 10. O-O Be7 11. Ng3 O-O 12. Bf5 $16 {White is just better.}) (8... Bc5 {This move looks active, but it doesn't go to the point because White is able to develop in a desired way.} 9. O-O O-O 10. Nc3 h6 11. Nge4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 f5 13. Bf3 e4 14. Be2 $16 {d2-d3 next.}) (8... Be7 $6 {is too passive, after} 9. Nc3 O-O 10. O-O h6 11. Nf3 $16 {Black should lose an extra tempo to defend the e5 pawn.}) (8... Bd6 9. O-O O-O {Black tries to play without the inclusion of the moves Nd5-Nf3 but this goes in White's favor.} (9... Nd5 $1 10. Nf3 {Transposes into the next chapters, but White could also consider 10.Ne4!?.}) 10. Nc3 h6 11. Nge4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Bc7 {Black's idea is f7-f5.} 13. Ng3 f5 14. Re1 $16 {Of course Black cannot play f5-f4 because the e4 square would be too strong for White, but also after e5-e4 White can play Bf1 followed by d2-d3. If Black doesn't do anything we can continue with b3-Bb2.}) (8... Nd5 {is Black's main move, and will be analyzed in the next chapters.}) 9. Nh3 $5 {Is my main recommendation, the point is to avoid the concrete lines arising after 9.Ne4, where it will be easier for our opponents to prepare.} (9. Ne4 {Is White's main move, here Black is forced to play} f5 10. Be2 $1 {An important tactical detail. Funny enough White's best reaction against f7-f5 is again Be2!} h5 11. h3 fxe4 12. hxg4 {In this very strange-looking position Black's path is very narrow, one mistake and he can be immediately lost.} Bc5 $1 {Black's only move. And now White has a choice.} 13. b4 {The most common move in practice.} (13. Nc3 Qd4 14. O-O O-O (14... Rf8 $2 15. b4 $1 {You can see from the following line why 14...00 was much better.} Rxf2 16. bxc5 Rxf1+ 17. Kxf1 Bxg4 {And now if Black would have played 14...00, then Rf8+ would be a deadly threat, and Black would have been already winning. Here White is winning after} 18. Bxg4 $18) (14... hxg4 $2 15. d3 e3 16. Bxe3 Qd8 17. g3 $1 {Only move, but an easy one, against Qh4-Qh1 mate ideas.} Bxe3 18. fxe3 Qg5 19. Kg2 $16) 15. Qe1 hxg4 16. d3 exd3 17. Bxd3 Rxf2 $1 (17... g3 $2 {Would be a mistake.} 18. Be3 gxf2+ 19. Bxf2 Rxf2 20. Rxf2 Bb6 21. Ne4 $18) 18. Qxf2 Qxf2+ 19. Rxf2 g3 20. Ne4 gxf2+ 21. Kf1 {After this long forced line, we arrive at an endgame which is probably more pleasant to play from the White side because Black's pawn structure is potentially vulnerable, but for the moment White needs to think about how to regain the missing f2 pawn, and in the while, Black should be able to activate his pieces to obtain a dynamically equal position.}) 13... Qd4 {Black has to follow the main line and find all the best moves.} (13... Bxb4 {Black is taking a pawn but now his bishop is not pressuring anymore White's f2 pawn.} 14. Nc3 Qd4 15. gxh5 $14 {With good chances for White.}) 14. bxc5 O-O 15. O-O Qxa1 16. Nc3 {And now Black must find} e3 $3 17. gxh5 exf2+ 18. Rxf2 Rxf2 19. Kxf2 Be6 20. Ba3 Rf8+ 21. Ke1 Qxd1+ 22. Bxd1 {According to the engine White is slightly better (+0,25) . Black's best moves are g6 or e4, both are pawn sacrifices and it might be not easy to play them over the board. Difficult to say something too clever about this endgame, you can analyze and play it if you like, it will be funny, but I am sure that objectively Black is fine here.}) 9... Bd6 $1 (9... Bc5 {Is the most common move, but in my opinion, d6 is the right square for Black's bishop.} 10. Nc3 O-O 11. O-O {We managed to complete our development and now we just need to solve our Nh3 issue. A typical operation will be to play Kh1, followed by Ng1.} h6 {Black is preparing Nf6 with the idea to attack our Nh3 when we will not be able to play Ng5.} (11... Nf6 {Black attacks our Nh3, but allows} 12. Ng5 $16 {Nge4 next.}) (11... f5 12. Be2 $14 {We want to play d3.}) 12. Kh1 $1 {For the moment we cannot play Ng1 because f2 is hanging, but if Black will play Nf6 back then Ng1 becomes a possibility.} Nf6 (12... Bd4 13. f3 Nf6 14. Nf2 $14) 13. Ng1 $14 {f3-Nge2-Ng3 next.}) (9... f5 10. Be2 $16 {A typical reaction against f7-f5. Now we just want to play our standard moves 00-Kh1-Ng1-d3-Nc3.}) 10. Nc3 $1 (10. O-O $6 Nxh2 $1 11. Kxh2 e4+ 12. Kg1 exd3 $15) 10... O-O (10... f5 11. Be2 $14 {As we have already seen many times, this is our typical reaction when Black plays f7-f5.}) 11. O-O {And now Black needs to go for a concrete line.} e4 $14 {There have been no over-the-board games in this position.} (11... Nxh2 $6 {Would be a mistake now because of} 12. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Kxh2 $16) 12. Nxe4 Bxh2+ 13. Kh1 Bc7 14. f4 $14 {We have a complicated position that according to the engine, it's still better for White (+0,30 is the evaluation) . Compared to the normal positions Black has sacrificed his important central 'e' pawn, but our king is slightly weaker now. We can continue with b3-Bb2.} *

