1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8. Bd3 Nd5 {Black's main move and a very serious one with more than 2.000 games that were played from here.} 9. Nf3 Bd6 ({The immediate} 9... Nf4 {is not so great because White can play} 10. Bf1 $1 {and we are ready for d2-d4 or d2-d3 with the idea to take Black's knight with our c1 bishop.} e4 (10... Bd6 11. d4 $1 e4 12. Ne5 $16) 11. d3 $1 exf3 12. Bxf4 Qf6 {is the critical line.} 13. Qxf3 Qxb2 14. Qe2+ Be6 15. Qe5 $1 {Forcing the queen exchange.} (15. Be5 $6 Qc1+ 16. Qd1 {Socko-Bartel 2019} Bb4+ $14 17. c3 Qb2 $13) 15... Bb4+ (15... Qxc2 $4 16. Qxa5 $18) 16. Kd1 Qxe5 (16... Nc4 $4 17. dxc4 Rd8+ 18. Bd3 Rd4 19. Qb8+ Ke7 {Arjun-Raahul 2021} 20. Qb7+ $14 Rd7 21. Be5 $18) 17. Bxe5 O-O 18. Be2 {Where Black doesn't have enough compensation for the missing pawn.}) (9... Qc7 {Transposes to a line analyzed in the next Chapter.}) 10. O-O {Now Black has two conceptually different choices: 10..00 with the idea to continue with f7-f5 and play for some kingside attack, 10...Nf4 with the idea to take our bishop on d3 and spoil White's structure. Let's start in this chapter to examine the latter.} Nf4 11. Nc3 {Now White is threatening Be2 because Black will not be able to play e5-e4 anymore.} Nxd3 (11... O-O $6 {Allows the just mentioned idea} 12. Be2 $1 {And Black is not able to play e5-e4 ideas because of the inclusion of the moves Nc3-00. It's completely clear that White is in good shape from the theoretical point of view, but let's check some high-level games.} Bg4 (12... c5 {A typical move that is played when Black wants to bring back his a5 knight into the game.} 13. d3 Nxe2+ (13... Ng6 14. Nd2 $1 Be6 15. Nc4 $16 {Ragger-Piorun 2021.}) 14. Qxe2 Bb7 15. Ne4 Nc6 16. Be3 f5 17. Nxc5 Bxc5 18. Bxc5 $16 {Shankland - L'Ami 2015.}) 13. d3 Nxe2+ 14. Qxe2 f5 15. h3 Bh5 16. g4 $1 {A move that has been played for the first time in the game Van Foreest-Carlsen 2020.} fxg4 17. Ng5 Qd7 18. Nce4 {Preparing Nxd6 or Ng3 ideas.} Be7 (18... h6 $14 {Probably Black's best move in the position.} 19. Nxd6 Qxd6 20. hxg4 hxg5 21. gxh5 $14 {We will continue with Bd2-Rae1.}) 19. Ng3 Bg6 20. Qxg4 Qxg4 21. hxg4 c5 22. N5e4 $14 {Van Foreest-Carlsen 2020.}) (11... f5 $6 {is punished by the strong deflection} 12. b4 $1 {and Black has nothing better than} Bxb4 13. Nxe5 $16 {, where we traded the important e5 pawn.}) 12. cxd3 O-O {We reach a very important position where it's crucial to remember the exact lines. I will try to keep it as simple as possible to help you remember everything. Keep in mind that according to the engine, Black will have very often decent positions, but from the practical point of view, those positions are difficult to play, and also Black needs to remember a lot in order to achieve them. Very recently even an opening machine like Fabiano Caruana lost immediately with the Black pieces in a classical game against Hikaru Nakamura.} 13. Re1 {Very logical move. We play Re1 not only to put pressure against the e5 pawn but also with the idea that when Black plays Ba6-Bxd3 it will not come with tempo against our Rf1.} (13. Ne4 Bc7 $1 14. Qc2 c5 $1 15. Qxc5 Ba6 $13) 13... Re8 {In most of the games Black is playing Re8 soon or later.} (13... f6 14. d4 $5 exd4 15. Ne4 $14 {We will just continue with d2-d3 and if Black plays c6-c5 then b3-Ba3.}) (13... c5 {Black's idea is to bring back to the game his Na5 by playing Nc6.} 14. b3 $1 {Whenever Black plays c6-c5 we are ready to continue with b3-Ba3-Ne4-Rc1 to put pressure against Black's c5 pawn.} (14. Nxe5 $6 {We are not ready to take the central pawn because we need first to finish our queenside development. Now after} Bb7 $44 {Black has a good compensation for the 2 missing pawns.}) 14... Nc6 (14... f6 {An alternative way to defend the e5 pawn.} 15. Ba3 Nc6 $6 16. Ne4 $14 {In the same position but with Re8 instead of f6 Black is continuing with Bf8, here this is not possible.} Be7 17. Bxc5 f5 18. Bxe7 $1 {The main difference is that now we are attacking Black's queen, While if Black's bishop would have been on f8 Black would have continued with fxe4! This is an important detail to remember.} Qxe7 19. Qc1 $1 Bb7 20. Qc4+ Kh8 21. Nc5 $18) (14... Re8 {Transposes into 13... Re8.}) 15. Ba3 Bg4 (15... Ba6 $6 {Black will take our d3 pawn, but it costs him 2 very important tempi.} 16. Ne4 Bxd3 17. Nxd6 Qxd6 18. Rc1 $14) (15... Re8 {Transposes to 13..:Re8, as always.}) 16. h3 Bh5 {Comparing to 16...Bxf3, here Black wants to play on the kingside but keeps his light-squares bishop.} (16... Bxf3 {Black gives up his light square bishop in order to build a fast attack against our king.} 17. Qxf3 Nd4 18. Qd1 f5 19. Na4 $5 {We are using our tempo to put pressure against Black's c5 pawn.} Qg5 (19... Rc8 $6 {Black shouldn't waste time to defend his c5 pawn.} 20. Rc1 $16) 20. Bxc5 Bxc5 21. Nxc5 Rf6 22. Re3 $1 {An important defensive idea.} Rh6 23. Rg3 Qf6 24. Qf1 $36 {I really like this move. Our idea is that when one day Black will play f4-f3 after he plays fxg2 we are ready to take on g2 with our queen.}) 17. Rc1 f5 18. Nb5 $1 Nd4 (18... Be7 $5 {A new move that has been played in a correspondence game one year ago.} 19. Bxc5 Bxc5 20. Rxc5 Nb4 21. Rexe5 Nxd3 22. Rcd5 Nxe5 23. Rxd8 Raxd8 {We have a very complex position where White is 2 pawns up but with precise moves, Black should be able to hold.}) (18... e4 $6 {This push seems appealing.} 19. dxe4 Ne5 $1 {is engine's move} (19... fxe4 20. Nxd6 Bxf3 21. gxf3 Qxd6 22. Rxe4 {Our king seems open, but there is no way to get to him.} Ne5 23. Bxc5 Qg6+ 24. Rg4 $1 Nxg4 25. hxg4 $16 {Where we have more than enough compensation.}) 20. Nxd6 Bxf3 21. gxf3 Nd3 $1 {Important, since ...Qd6 was met by the powerful d4!} 22. Qe2 {And a forcing line ensues where White is ahead at the end:} Qxd6 23. Bxc5 $1 Qg6+ (23... Nxc5 $2 24. Qc4+ $18) 24. Kh2 fxe4 25. Bxf8 Rxf8 26. Rg1 Qd6+ 27. Rg3 Nxc1 28. Qc4+ $1 Kh8 29. Qxc1 Rxf3 30. Kg2 Rxg3+ 31. fxg3 $16 {And White has the task of converting his extra pawn.}) 19. Nbxd4 cxd4 20. Bxd6 Qxd6 21. Qc2 Bxf3 22. gxf3 $36 {Our structure looks terrible, but in fact, we are still a pawn up, and our rooks are much better placed. Now we want to play a move like Qc5 or Qe5 and we will play also against Black's e5 pawn.}) 14. Ne4 {For the moment we don't play b2-b3, but we wait for another move because maybe we will be able to play b2-b4 immediately if Black is inaccurate.} c5 (14... f6 $2 15. d4 $16) (14... Bc7 {Allows the typical idea} 15. b4 $1 Nb7 16. Bb2 Qxd3 17. Rc1 Bd7 18. Nfg5 $16 {Low-Lee 2018.}) (14... Bf8 15. b4 $1 Nb7 (15... Bxb4 16. Qa4 $16) 16. Bb2 Bg4 (16... Qxd3 17. Nxe5 $14) 17. h3 Bxf3 18. Qxf3 Bxb4 19. Qg3 $16 {Prag-Niemann 2022}) 15. b3 Bf8 $1 (15... Ba6 $6 {As it usually happens, Black wants to take our d3 pawn but the loss of tempis is much more an important factor.} 16. Bb2 Nc6 17. Nfg5 $16) (15... Nc6 16. Ba3 Bg4 {Black is trying to save a move on Bf8, but this is not a good strategy:} 17. h3 Bh5 18. Rc1 $16) 16. Ba3 {Now we have the main position of the 10...Nf4 line. Now Black has a choice if he wants to play the concrete but very risky 16...f5, which has been played so far only in correspondence chess, or the easier-to-understand 16... Nc6 has been played in a lot of high-level games. Also, there is a third path 16...Nb7 with only 3 played games.} Nc6 (16... Nb7 17. Rc1 Qa5 {An idea that was tried by GM Aryan Tari in 2023.} 18. Bb2 f6 19. Nh4 $40 {I like this move that has the idea to open the position by playing next f2-f4.}) (16... f5 {This move has been played only in correspondence chess so far. Black holds but he needs to remember really a lot.} 17. Ng3 (17. Nxc5 {Even after this move Black has a very narrow path to survive.} e4 18. Qe2 Bxc5 19. Bxc5 Ba6 20. Nd4 Nb7 21. Nc6 Qf6 22. Ne7+ Kh8 23. Ba3 Bxd3 24. Qe3 f4 25. Qh3 $11) 17... Nc6 18. Rc1 (18. Qc2 $14 {Could be an interesting idea because if our opponent doesn't understand the difference and just plays again 18...f4, after 19.Ne4 Black doesn't have anymore the Bg4 idea because now our Nf3 is not pinned. According to the engine Black's best solution against 18.Qc2 is Ba6.}) 18... f4 $1 {Black really needs to play it.} 19. Ne4 Bg4 20. h3 Bh5 21. g4 $1 {An important move that ruins our structure but allows us to unpin our Nf3.} fxg3 22. Nxg3 Bxf3 (22... Bg6 {Is risky even according to the engine} 23. Bxc5 Qd5 24. b4 Nxb4 25. Bxb4 Bxb4 26. Nxe5 Bxd2 27. Qxd2 Rxe5 28. Rxe5 Qxe5 29. d4 $14 {Black can survive, but we can play on forever thanks to the extra pawn.}) 23. Qxf3 Nd4 {Here White has 2 possible moves: Qg4 or Qh5.} 24. Qg4 (24. Qh5 c4 $1 {Black needs to know this move otherwise he is worse.} 25. Bb2 cxb3 26. Bxd4 Qxd4 27. axb3 Qxd3 $11) 24... Qa5 $1 25. Bb2 Qxa2 26. Bxd4 exd4 27. Rxe8 Rxe8 28. Ne4 {Maybe it's a little bit unpleasant to play from the Black side, but objectively the position is equal.}) 17. Rc1 Nb4 (17... f5 $2 {In this lesson, we are checking a lot of engine moves, but in a practical game, even one of the best players in the world can lose immediately.} 18. Nxc5 Qd5 19. Qc2 $18 {Happened in the famous game Nakamura-Caruana June 2023.}) 18. Bxb4 cxb4 {Now we have 2 possible directions, but first let's take a break to comment on the position. Black has the bishop's pair while we have 2 knights, and this factor itself provides him good compensation. Our main hope is not really our extra pawn, but our pieces activity.} 19. Nc5 (19. Ng3 Bb7 (19... Qxd3 $6 20. Nxe5 $14 {Of course we are happy to have exchanged our d3 pawn for Black's e5 one.}) 20. Nxe5 Qd6 $1 (20... f6 $6 {Again we can see that over the board it's very easy to make a mistake.} 21. Nc4 Qd5 22. Re4 $14 {And White won a nice game in Sanikidze-Urkedal 2021.}) 21. Nc4 Qd5 22. Re4 {Comparing to 20... f6, here Black hasn't weakened some important squares. Of course for a human it's not easy to understand such a detail, but according to the engine here Black has a much higher chances to hold.} Qxd3 23. Rxe8 Rxe8 24. Ne3 {Still I would take White, as they used to say in the Soviet Union chess school " You have compensation but you don't have the pawn".}) 19... Qd5 (19... Bf5 {A less common move, but not a bad one.} 20. Nxe5 Rc8 {Now White has two interesting tries.} 21. Qf3 (21. Na4 Rxc1 22. Qxc1 Qd5 23. Qa1 $13 {Now Black is 2 pawns down and he doesn't really want to give up his bishop f5 in order to recover one of the missing pawns. What Black should do is to play useful moves and try to show that the bishop's pair is itself a good compensation for the missing 'd' pawns.}) 21... g6 22. g4 Bxc5 23. gxf5 Rxe5 24. Rxe5 Bxf2+ 25. Kxf2 Rxc1 26. Qf4 $13 {According to the engine Black can hold, but in a practical game everything can happen.}) 20. d4 Bg4 21. h3 Bxf3 22. Qxf3 Qxf3 (22... Qxd4 $6 23. Rc4 Qxd2 24. Rd1 Qxa2 25. Rd7 $36) 23. gxf3 exd4 24. Rxe8 Rxe8 25. Nd3 {Now the type of position is changed. Black has recovered the missing pawn but we have a good knight against Black's potentially bad bishop. It's clear that we are having a 2 results endgame and Black needs to play well in order to bring home the desired draw.} *

