1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8. Bd3 Nd5 9. Nf3 Bd6 10. O-O {We are missing one last line, but a very important one.} O-O 11. Re1 {Again we have an easy move to remember.} f5 $1 {This move was shown for the first time by the new engines of the year 2013. For the last 10 years it has been considered Black's best continuation without any doubts.} (11... Qc7 {Black defends the e5 pawn but gives an important tempo for White.} 12. c4 $1 Nf4 13. Bf1 {White is ready for d2-d4 if Black plays another slow move.} Bg4 14. d3 Ne6 15. Bd2 $14 {White prepares b2-b4 and if Black plays c6-c5 then after Nc3 his d5 square will be too weak. White is just better.}) (11... Bg4 12. h3 Bxf3 {Black gives up his light squares bishop but he hopes to solve the problems with a concrete move.} (12... Bh5 13. Bf5 $1 {With the idea Bg4 to unpin our Nf3.} Qf6 14. Bg4 Bxg4 15. hxg4 Qg6 16. Nh4 Qf6 17. Nf5 $16 {Navara-Beljavsky 2009.}) 13. Qxf3 f5 {The critical continuation, but we are still better here.} 14. Bxf5 {Using the fact that after g6 we can play Be6+.} Qe7 {Now we have to find an accurate move.} 15. c4 $1 {We have to diminish Black's initiative and rescue our pinned bishop on f5.} g6 (15... Nxc4 16. d3 Ncb6 17. Qe4 $14) 16. cxd5 Rxf5 17. Qe4 {And it seems that White will have the upper hand in the following continuations:} Qf7 18. dxc6 Rf4 $1 (18... Rxf2 $2 19. Nc3 Rf4 20. Qd5 $18) 19. Qe3 Nxc6 20. Nc3 Nd4 21. Ne4 $1 Bb4 (21... Nc2 $2 22. Nxd6 $18) 22. Qd3 Rd8 23. Kh1 $14 {Black has some compensation, but not enough for the 2 missing pawns.}) (11... Re8 {This is Black's old main line, and it's a very logical move because it defends the e5 pawn and also prepares the e5-e4 push in some cases.} 12. Nc3 f5 13. Bf1 e4 14. Nxd5 cxd5 (14... exf3 $2 15. Rxe8+ Qxe8 16. Nc3 fxg2 17. Bxg2 $16) 15. Nd4 {Black has a lot of central pawns, but we have achieved the important d4 square for our knight.} Qf6 {The most logical continuation.} (15... Nc4 $14 {is an interesting try, to get a complex game, but White is better and in my opinion, not risking anything.} 16. d3 Ne5 17. h3 $14 {Prophylaxis against Ng4 and Black still has to prove where is his compensation.}) 16. c3 $14 {next we play d2-d3 and practice has shown that Black doesn't have enough compensation for the missing pawn.} Bd7 17. d3 Nc6 18. Qb3 $14 {[%cal Rc6d4,Gb3d5] Puts pressure on the diagonal, and Black is suffering.}) 12. Nxe5 Qf6 13. Nf3 g5 $1 {In this position it's all about concrete moves and if Black is fast enough to create a strong counterplay. I can already tell you that from the engine point of view yes, but we need to understand how the following variations are working from the practical point of view.} 14. c4 Nf4 15. Bf1 g4 16. d4 $1 gxf3 17. Qxf3 Ne6 {After a long forced sequence of moves we have achieved a position where White has 3 pawns for the missing piece. In addition Black's Na5 is out of the game. We need to go much further from here to understand what's going on.} 18. Qc3 {Attacking Black's Na5. Now Black has 4 possible continuations, and we need to have some ideas against each of them. The position is complicated and good for 3 results, but the better-prepared player will have higher chances to prevail.} Nxd4 {In my opinion this is Black's best attempt from the practical point of view.} (18... c5 {A rare move, but has been played by the young Vincent Keymer one year ago.} 19. Qxa5 Nxd4 {Moussard-Keymer 2023} 20. Qd2 $1 Qg6 $14 (20... Qh4 $6 21. Qg5+ Qxg5 22. Bxg5 Nc2 23. Nc3 Nxa1 24. Rxa1 $14 {Happened in the game Bick-Quesada 2023. Black has won this game but mainly because he had 300 rating points more than his opponent. Objectively speaking White is on the top and he can continue with Be3-Na4-b3 putting pressure also against Black's c5 pawn. All in all a knight and 2 pawns are good enough in the endgame against the rook.}) (20... Kh8 $2 21. f4 $16) 21. Kh1 Bxh2 $1 22. Qg5 (22. Kxh2 {Leads to a draw most likely after} f4 $1 {Introducing the threat of ...Nf3} 23. Nc3 Nf3+ $1 24. gxf3 Qh6+ 25. Kg1 Qg6+ $11 (25... Qg5+ $4 26. Bg2 Bh3 27. Qd5+ $18)) 22... Bc7 23. Na3 a6 24. Qxg6+ hxg6 25. Bh6 $1 Rd8 (25... Rf7 26. Re8+ Kh7 27. Be3 $14) 26. Bg5 Rd7 27. Re8+ Kf7 28. Rae1 $14) (18... Bc7 $6 19. d5 $1 cxd5 20. cxd5 Qxc3 21. Nxc3 Nd4 22. Rd1 Be5 23. Bd2 $14 {Three pawns are stronger here than Black's piece, also according to the engine White has +0,40.}) (18... Qh4 19. h3 c5 $1 (19... Nxd4 $2 {Gokerkan-Keymer 2023, again we can see how easy is to mix up moves in these lines.} 20. c5 $14 Bc7 21. b4 Nb7 22. Bc4+ Kg7 23. Bb2 Rd8 24. Nd2 $18 {And Black is busted.}) 20. Qxa5 Nxd4 21. Nc3 f4 {Here White has tried 22.Re4, but after 22...Nf3! Black is fine according to the engines, he can force a draw by repetition in deep variations.} 22. Rd1 $14 {My new idea.} Bb7 {Is Black's best and most natural move, and here I want to go for} (22... Nf3+ $4 {It's very easy for Black to go Nf3 also here, but now it doesn't work.} 23. gxf3 Bxh3 24. Ne4 $1 {Comparing to the 22.Re4 line, now White has the important e4 square for his knight.} Rf7 25. Qc3 Rg7+ 26. Qxg7+ Kxg7 27. Rxd6 $18 {White has too much material for the missing queen.}) 23. Rxd4 $1 cxd4 24. c5 $1 Be7 {is Black's best defence, but it's not human play at all in my opinion, look how the engine forces a draw:} (24... Rf5 $2 25. Qb5 $1 dxc3 26. Qxb7 Rb8 27. Qxa7 $18) (24... Qh5 {Pinning the d5 pawn because Qa5 would be hanging.} 25. Qb5 Qxc5 26. Qxb7 dxc3 27. bxc3 $36 {We have only a pawn for the missing exchange but I like White's position because it's very easy to see how our bishop's pair can become deadly strong against Black's weak king.}) 25. Qc7 Bxg2 $1 26. Bxg2 Rae8 $3 27. Bd5+ Kh8 28. Ne4 Bd8 29. Qd6 Be7 $11 {I don't know how many years it will take to see this happening in an over-the-board game.}) (18... Nb7 {Is Black's most common move, and a very logical one as he is just retreating a hanging piece.} 19. c5 Bc7 20. b4 {White can play for b4-b5 or for d4-d5, depending on the situation.} a5 $1 {By far Black's best move.} (20... Bd7 $2 21. d5 cxd5 {Fier-Perdomo 2021} 22. Qxf6 $14 Rxf6 23. Nc3 $18 {Black's pieces are terribly placed and White is already winning according to the engine.}) (20... Qxd4 $2 {Would be a huge mistake.} 21. Qxd4 Nxd4 22. Bc4+ {Black is in deep trouble.}) (20... Nbd8 21. Bb2 Nf4 {Black would like to place a knight on d5, but White is just in time to create serious problems.} 22. Qb3+ $1 Nd5 (22... Be6 23. d5 $18) 23. Nc3 Be6 24. Bc4 Qf7 25. Rxe6 $18) 21. b5 cxb5 22. Bxb5 {Black has managed to exchange his weak c6 pawn for White's strong b4 pawn. But the danger is not over yet and he needs to play some other strong moves to reach an acceptable position.} a4 $1 {Black is freeing the a5 square for his bishop, or for his knight in case we play Bc4.} (22... Qxd4 $6 23. Bc4 Qxc3 24. Nxc3 Nbxc5 25. Ba3 $16 {Too many pins.}) (22... Nxd4 $6 23. Bc4+ Be6 24. Bb2 Nxc5 25. Rxe6 Ndxe6 26. Qxf6 Rxf6 27. Bxf6 $14 {Risk-free endgame for White.}) 23. Bc4 Na5 (23... Kh8 $6 {Macias-Arabidze 2023. In an over-the-board game, Black played a logical move, but here White has already good chances:} 24. Bb2 $1 Ba5 25. Qc1 Bxe1 26. Bxe6 $1 Bxf2+ 27. Kxf2 Qh4+ 28. Kg1 Bxe6 29. d5+ Kg8 30. Qc3 Qf6 31. Qxf6 Rxf6 32. c6 $14) (23... Ba5 {Leads to a forced variation:} 24. Qg3+ Kh8 25. Rxe6 $1 Bxe6 26. Bf4 $1 Bxc4 27. Be5 Rae8 28. Bxf6+ Rxf6 29. Na3 Bd5 30. Qd3 $14 {From the human point of view the position is a total mess, from the engine's point of view White has a bit higher chance. Our idea is to continue Nc4 and then see if Nxa5 or Ne5 or Nd6. No games here but only a lot of questions :)} (30. f3 {has been played in the game Palcertz-Zanan 2022, but here White's Qg3 is misplaced and very important that White is not ready for Nc4 ideas.})) 24. Bd5 $1 {Of course we need to preserve our light squares bishop.} Rb8 25. Qe3 Re8 26. Nc3 {Has been tried in the only game that has reached this position.} (26. Bd2 $14 {Can be interesting, with the idea to develop Nb1 on a3.} Bd7 27. Na3 Nc6 28. Rad1 $13 {Very complex position with all three results possible.}) (26. c6 $5 {An other possible direction, I am too scared to look into it :)}) 26... Bd7 $1 (26... Kf8 $6 {Janik-Nasuta 2021.} 27. Ba3 $18 {You can see how difficult is to play these positions over the board, also for young and strong grand masters.}) 27. Bd2 Kg7 28. Qh3 Rb2 (28... Nxd4 $6 29. Ne4 $36) 29. Re2 {My engine shows that 29...a3 is Black's best move, and I decided to stop here.}) 19. c5 {Again Black has a choice.} Be5 {Is more concrete. If I were to play from the Black side, I would take this direction.} (19... Bc7 {Black defends the hanging Na5.} 20. b4 Rb8 (20... Nb7 $2 21. Bb2 Rd8 22. Bc4+ Kf8 23. Nd2 $18 {Black will not survive against our very strong bishops.}) (20... Be5 $2 {is a mistake but with one trick} 21. Rxe5 $1 Qxe5 22. Bb2 Rd8 23. Nd2 $18 {[%cal Bg1h1] Or 23.Na3. The trick is to not take the knight on a5, as after ... Rb8 Black gets some counterplay.}) 21. f4 $5 {Against Be5.} (21. bxa5 Be5 $1 22. Bc4+ Kh8 $13) 21... Be6 (21... Qg7 22. Kh1 Ne6 23. Bb2 Bxf4 $1 (23... Qxc3 {It's tempting to exchange the queens, but it's not Black's best solution.} 24. Bxc3 Nb7 25. Bc4 Nbd8 26. g3 $14 {Again our bishops are very strong. We will continue with Nd2-Nf3 and it's very difficult to play from the Black side.}) 24. Qxg7+ Nxg7 25. Bc3 Re8 $3 (25... Nb7 $2 26. Bc4+ Kh8 27. Re7 $16) 26. Rxe8+ Nxe8 27. bxa5 Be6 28. Na3 $36 {We have recovered the piece but now Black's pieces are well placed, and for this reason, he should be able to hold, but we are still on the better side.}) 22. bxa5 {I like to take back the missing piece, and now Black's most precise move is} (22. Bb2 Rfd8 23. Na3 Bxf4 $13 {Cumming-Sousa 2023.}) 22... Rf7 $3 {And I think that it's a very good moment to stop because I doubt Rf7 will ever be played. According to the engine, it's 0.00 after many moves like Kh1, Bd2 or Qd3.}) 20. Qxa5 f4 $1 {This idea was offered by the strong English GM Gaiwain Jones. Only 2 games were played from this position.} (20... Nc2 {The logical continuation.} 21. Bg5 $1 {We want to trade our Bc1 for Black's active Be5.} Qxg5 22. Rxe5 Nxa1 23. Bc4+ Kh8 24. f4 $1 Qf6 (24... Qxf4 25. Qc3 $18) 25. Nd2 $36 {We are down a full rook, but all our pieces are very well placed. Very likely we will take back Black's Na1 and this means that the material will be fine very soon.}) 21. Nd2 (21. Bd2 $4 f3 22. g3 Ne2+ 23. Bxe2 fxe2 24. f4 Bxf4 25. Bxf4 Qd4+ 26. Kg2 Qe4+ 27. Kf2 Bh3 $19 {0-1 Varney,Z (2045) -Schneider,J (2342) Olympiad Women-44 Chennai 2022 (9. 4) This game was impressive enough to make us pay serious attention to the 20.. .f4 variation.}) 21... Bf5 (21... f3 $2 {Doesn't work anymore.} 22. Ne4 $1 Qg6 23. g3 Ne2+ 24. Bxe2 fxe2 25. Qa4 $1 {And the difference is evident with 21. Bd2.} Bg4 26. Ng5 Qh5 27. Qc4+ Kh8 28. h3 $18 {We will end up just being 2 pawns up in the end.}) 22. Qa4 $14 {This is my idea that is not mentioned by Jones.} (22. Nc4 {Jones analyzes only this move, and now Black has a fantastic idea} Nf3+ 23. Kh1 $1 (23. gxf3 $4 Qg5+ 24. Kh1 Rf7 25. Bh3 Rg7 26. Bxf4 Qxf4 $19 {0-1 Dere,P (2191) -Subhayan,K (2385) Bhubaneswar SOA op 1st 2024 (6) Is another bad game for the White pieces.}) 23... Nxe1 24. Qxe1 Bd4 25. Bxf4 Rae8 $11 {According to the engine all the complications will end up in a forced draw.}) 22... Nc2 {Black's most logical move.} (22... Qg7 23. Rxe5 $1 Qxe5 24. Nb3 Ne2+ 25. Bxe2 Qxe2 26. Bd2 $14) (22... Kh8 {Black's second best move according to the engine. The idea is to free the g8 square for Black's rook.} 23. Nc4 (23. Rxe5 Qxe5 24. Nb3 Nf3+ $1 25. gxf3 Rg8+ 26. Kh1 Bg4 $3 27. Nd4 Qe1 28. Bxf4 Qxa1 29. Be5+ Rg7 30. Bxg7+ Kxg7 31. Kg2 Bh3+ 32. Kxh3 Qxf1+ 33. Kg3 Qg1+ 34. Kh3 $11 {If Black finds all these strong moves we should be happy with the draw.}) 23... Nf3+ 24. Kh1 Nxe1 25. Nxe5 Rad8 $3 {Black's only move and this is already a very good practical chance for us.} 26. Bxf4 Bc2 27. Qa3 Qxf4 28. Qc3 Qd4 29. Qxd4 Rxd4 30. Rxe1 $11 {But even here I would say that a lot of fight is left in the position. Black already has a big decision to make: take on f2 or protect the c6 pawn.}) 23. Nf3 Nxe1 24. Nxe5 Qxe5 (24... Nxg2 25. Bxg2 Qxe5 26. Bd2 $13 {Completely unclear, but I like White because after Bc3 we will have a very strong dark squares bishop.}) 25. Bxf4 {This line is very shaky for Black, but thanks to some only moves he is able to equalize.} Qe4 26. Qxe4 Bxe4 27. Rxe1 Rxf4 28. g3 Kh8 $3 29. Bc4 Rff8 30. Rxe4 Rae8 31. Rxe8 Rxe8 32. Kf1 $11 {Some final thoughts about the 3...Nf6 4.Ng5 variation. First, 1.e4 e5 equalizes! From the theoretical point of view, we have another confirmation about this thing. Second, the Italian 3.Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 variation is for sure a very strong weapon for White. When I was playing 3. ..Nf6 from the Black side I was always praying that my opponent would not play 4.Ng5 because I knew I would have to remember a lot of forced lines to make a draw, and if I make one mistake I can immediately lose. Third, What I have shown you is by far not a refutation of Black's systems. I have tried to give you new practical ideas considering the current state of theory and all the existing published material about this line. I hope you enjoyed seeing this opening and I hope that you will enjoy even more to play it during your games!} *

