{Welcome to the Fast test section. Don't forget that to make this lesson useful it's better if you check it in the video. This PGN file should just remain as a recap of the asked questions.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 {I decided to test you in the most theoretical 3...Nf6 4.Ng5 line.} 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 (5... Nxd5 6. Nxf7 Kxf7 7. Qf3+ Ke6 8. Nc3 Ncb4 9. O-O c6 {Test 1, White to play. Find the best move in the position.} 10. d4 $1 {This really has to be played, otherwise White is just worse. You can check the following complications in Chapter 9.}) (5... b5 {Test 2. White to move, Which is the only move that fights for an opening advantage?} 6. Bf1 $1 Nxd5 (6... Nd4 7. c3 Nxd5 8. cxd4 Qxg5 9. Bxb5+ Kd8 10. O-O Bb7 11. Qf3 {Test 3. This time it's Black to move. What is his only move that keeps the game going?} Rb8 $1 {Black defends his bishop and prepares some knight jump.} 12. dxe5 Ne3 13. Qh3 Qxg2+ 14. Qxg2 Nxg2 15. d4 $14 {More about the endgame in Chapter 10.}) 7. Bxb5 Bb7 8. d4 exd4 9. O-O Be7 10. Qh5 g6 11. Qh6 Qd7 12. Re1 {Test 4. What is Black's best move?} a6 $1 (12... Qf5 $2 {Would be bad immediately because of} 13. Bd3 $16 {That's why is really important for Black to include the move 12... a6.}) 13. Ba4 Qf5 {and hereafter the moves} 14. Nf3 O-O-O 15. Bxc6 Bxc6 16. Nxd4 Qf6 {comes my idea} 17. c3 $14) 6. Bb5+ c6 (6... Bd7 7. Qe2 Bd6 8. O-O {Test 5. What is Black's best move?} h6 $1 {It's really important to force White's Ng5 to retreat immediately to f3, otherwise after Nc3 we will have Nge4 options.} (8... O-O $6 9. Bxd7 Qxd7 10. Nc3 {and then we have Nge4 options.}) 9. Nf3 O-O 10. Bxd7 Qxd7 11. Nc3 c6 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Qxe5 cxd5 14. d4 Nc6 15. Qf4 Rae8 {Test 6. White to move. What is our best practical chance?} 16. Qd2 $5 {Defending the d4 pawn with the idea to continue Nd1 (or Nb5) followed by c2-c3. By playing Qd2 we make sure Black doesn't have Re4 ideas coming with tempo against our queen on f4.}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 {Test 7, explain the differences between Bd3 and Be2.} 8. Bd3 Nd5 9. Nf3 Bd6 10. O-O O-O (10... Nf4 11. Nc3 O-O $6 {Test 8. Why 11...00 is already not so precise?} 12. Be2 $1 {And compared to the immediate 11.Be2, Black now doesn't have e5-e4 ideas. Of course, Black had to continue with 11...Nxd3 and we have analyzed in great detail this position in Chapter 13.}) 11. Re1 f5 (11... Bg4 12. h3 Bh5 {Test 9. This position happened in the game Navara-Beljavsky. How White should continue?} 13. Bf5 $16 {By playing Bg4 on the next move White is solving in a very elegant way the Nf3 pin problem.}) 12. Nxe5 Qf6 13. Nf3 g5 14. c4 Nf4 15. Bf1 g4 16. d4 gxf3 17. Qxf3 Ne6 18. Qc3 Qh4 19. h3 c5 20. Qxa5 Nxd4 21. Nc3 f4 {Test 10, the most difficult one. Here I have offered you a new idea, do you remember which one and what was the idea behind it?} 22. Rd1 $5 {White has only tries 22.Re4 in practice. The difference here is that after} Nf3+ $4 23. gxf3 Bxh3 {We have the e4 square available for our knight.} 24. Ne4 $1 {, after} Rf7 25. Qc3 Rg7+ 26. Qxg7+ Kxg7 27. Rxd6 $18 {White has too much material for the missing queen and he is just winning.} *

