1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. e5 d5 7. Be2 {I like to play this line of the Max Lange more than 7.Bb5.} Ne4 8. cxd4 Bb4+ {is one of Black's option, now we have to play without the bishops pair.} 9. Bd2 Nxd2 10. Nbxd2 O-O 11. O-O Ne7 {is one of the moves.} 12. Nb3 (12. a3 {and going for the queenside expansion with b4-Nb3 is correct here, and analyzed in Chapter 7.}) 12... Ng6 13. g3 {To not allow ...Nf4 I don't think it is big weakness.} f6 14. a3 Be7 15. Rc1 c6 16. Nc5 {Got my knight to c5, but maybe Black is doing fine here already.} Bxc5 17. Rxc5 Bg4 18. Re1 {Hanging on to the pawn center is always important.} Bxf3 19. Bxf3 fxe5 20. dxe5 Qe7 21. Rc2 Rae8 22. Bh5 Qg5 23. e6 Rf6 24. Bxg6 {I released the tension and game ended in a draw.} (24. h4 $1 {was a super nice intermezzo, using that Nxh4 is not possible anymore because e8 is hanging.}) 24... Qxg6 25. e7 Rf7 26. Rce2 Qf6 27. Qa4 Rfxe7 28. Rxe7 Rxe7 29. Rxe7 Qxe7 30. Qxa7 Qe1+ 31. Kg2 Qe4+ 32. Kg1 Qe1+ 33. Kg2 Qe4+ 34. Kg1 Qe1+ 1/2-1/2

