1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. e5 d5 7. Be2 Ne4 8. cxd4 Bb6 9. Nc3 {We develop to c3 to not allow ...f6-exf6-Qxf6 as d5 is hanging.} O-O 10. O-O {I had many games here. We are playing around the e5 square.} Be6 {is a possible move. Black's idea is to defend the d5 pawn in order to continue with f6-exf6-Qxf6.} 11. Be3 {My idea is to play Bd3 and provoke ...Nxc3, that structure is good for White.} f6 12. exf6 Qxf6 13. Bd3 Nxc3 {Now I am happy with this concession, the structure is good and the bishop is dead on b6.} (13... Qg6 $14 {is the engine's defence that we analyze in Chapter 8.}) 14. bxc3 Bg4 15. Be2 {We go back and unpin.} Ne7 16. Ne5 {Immediately jump before it is not too late.} Bxe2 17. Qxe2 Qe6 18. f4 {Now I just want to fully expand on the kingside, in the game I got a very big advantage, but spoiled it at some point. But already here it is very very tough to play with Black.} Nf5 19. g4 {All going as planned.} Nxe3 20. Qxe3 Rae8 21. Rae1 c5 {Desperate way to look for counterplay.} 22. dxc5 Bc7 23. Qg3 d4 24. cxd4 Qxa2 {Here it is already a winning advantage for me, you can check the rest for yourself.} 25. Rb1 Qd5 26. Qb3 Qxb3 27. Rxb3 b6 28. c6 Rd8 29. Nd7 Rxf4 30. Rxf4 Bxf4 31. d5 Kf7 32. Ra3 Ke7 33. Rxa7 Kd6 34. Kg2 Kxd5 35. Nxb6+ Kxc6 36. Nc4 Kc5 1/2-1/2

