1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. e5 d5 7. Be2 Ne4 8. cxd4 Bb6 9. Nc3 O-O 10. O-O f6 {Opponent changed the move, now we have to take because ...Qxf6 is not possible as d5 pawn is hanging.} 11. exf6 Nxf6 {Black was forced to take this way, as ...Nxc3 is horrible as we already know.} 12. Bg5 {Going for the pin also seems interesting.} (12. h3 {is the nice prophylactic move, stopping ...Bg4 and then focusing on the Rc1-Na4-Bb5 plan. This is all analyzed in Chapter 8.}) 12... Bg4 13. Rc1 {Now a standard trick is we want to take Nxd5 when ...Qxd5 runs into a pin after Bc4!} Kh8 {Prophylaxis against the trick.} 14. Ne5 {Now again I take control of the e5 square. The rest of the game was easy, I was maybe playing not perfect, but opponent was very low on time.} Bxe2 15. Nxe2 Qd6 16. Bf4 {Black is in trouble here, you can check out the rest for yourself.} Qe6 17. Nxc6 bxc6 18. Be5 Ne4 19. Nf4 Qh6 20. Nd3 Rae8 21. b4 Nd2 22. Re1 Nc4 23. g3 Nxe5 24. Nxe5 Rxe5 25. Rxe5 Bxd4 26. Re2 Bxf2+ 27. Rxf2 Rxf2 28. Kxf2 Qxh2+ 29. Kf3 Qh5+ 30. Kg2 1-0

